Schwartz, 2002\n* ''Inescapable Questions: Autobiographical Notes'', Alija Izetbegovi\u0107, The Islamic Foundation, 2003\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[Chairman of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]|\n years=1990\u20131996|\n before=[[Nijaz Durakovi\u0107]]'''<br />''as '''Chairman of the Presidency of the Socialist Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina'' |\n after=[[\u017divko Radi\u0161i\u0107]]<br />Tripartite presidency\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Yugoslav wars}}\n{{Bosnian President}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Izetbegovic, Alija}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bosniak politicians]]\n[[Category:Bosniaks of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina Sunni Muslims]]\n[[Category:Lawyers]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina writers]]\n[[Category:Chairmen of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Grand Order of Queen Jelena recipients]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina politicians]]\n[[Category:Party of Democratic Action politicians]]\n[[Category:People from \u0160amac, Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Politicians of the Bosnian War]]\n[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:Sarajevo Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina people of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina people of World War II]]\n[[Category:Bosnian nationalism]]\n[[Category:Members of the Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n", "name_user": "Amanuensis Balkanicus", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life and education:the source you provided doesn't refute this)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alija_Izetbegovi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Kunal Kamra", "text_new": "{{Infobox comedian\n|birth_name=Kunal Kamra\n|birth_date=3rd October 1988\n|nationality=Indian\n|notable_works=Shut up Ya Kunal, Fresh Thoughts\n|website=http://www.kunalkamra.in\n}}\n\n'''Kunal Kamra''' is a comedian who is recognised for his [[observational comedy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/fashion-and-trends/kunal-kamra-talks-about-his-chance-encounter-with-stand-up-comedy/story-cvCxtPNT1oss0Ta2SwISVL.html|title=Kunal Kamra chance encounter with stand up comedy|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321044724/https://www.hindustantimes.com/fashion-and-trends/kunal-kamra-talks-about-his-chance-encounter-with-stand-up-comedy/story-cvCxtPNT1oss0Ta2SwISVL.html|archive-date=2019-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> and incisive political commentary.\n\nIn 2020, after an incident on [[IndiGo]] airlines where he confronted the Indian news anchor [[Arnab Goswami]], he was banned by five Indian Airlines.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/kunal-kamra-flight-ban-what-gets-you-on-a-no-fly-list/ban-on-comedian-kunal-kamra/slideshow/73759924.cms|title=Kunal Kamra flight ban: What gets you on a 'No-Fly' List}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nKunal Kamra was born on 3 October 1988, in [[Mahim]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/kunal-kamra-indian-comedian-riles-ruling-party-edgy-humour-180417065234329.html|title=Kunal Kamra birth place - Mahim|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321180823/https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/kunal-kamra-indian-comedian-riles-ruling-party-edgy-humour-180417065234329.html|archive-date=2019-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mumbai]], [[India]]. Kamra grew up in Mumbai, and joined [[Jai Hind College]] for a degree in [[commerce]]. He dropped in second year to start working as a production assistant in Prasoon Pandey\u2019s ad film production house Corcoise Films, where he stayed for eleven years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/kunal-kamra-on-his-shows-and-indian-stand-up-comedy/article19296076.ece|title=Murthy, Neeraja (2017-07-17). \"Bring your brains along\". The Hindu. Retrieved 22 May 2018.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015140436/https://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/kunal-kamra-on-his-shows-and-indian-stand-up-comedy/article19296076.ece|archive-date=15 October 2018|dead-url=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/C39AsWWaic7qvGsONZNCnJ/Kunal-Kamra-The-accidental-revolutionary.html|title=Kunal Kamra: The accidental revolutionary|last=Chatterjee|first=Suprateek|date=2018-03-16|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\nHe started performing as a standup comedian in 2013, with a gig at the Canvas Laugh Club in Mumbai.<ref name=\":2\" /> A clip of one of his gigs, uploaded on YouTube in 2017, lead to him receiving death threats for his satirical take on Indian hyper-nationalism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thequint.com/neon/shut-up-ya-kunal-kamra-comedian-political-review|title=\"Please Don't 'Shut Up Ya Kunal': Enjoying Politics Through Comedy\". The Quint. Retrieved 27 May 2018.|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015140428/https://www.thequint.com/neon/shut-up-ya-kunal-kamra-comedian-political-review|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He started his eponymous titled web-series ''Shut Up Ya Kunal'' in July 2017 along with Ramit Verma.<ref name=\":4\" /> The episodes typically feature a conversation with one or more invited guests, interposed with clips of news segments or debates, edited for humour.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/express-sunday-eye/dont-get-mad-get-funny-5093304/|title=D'souza, Dipti Nagpaul (11 March 2018). \"Don't Get Mad, Get Funny: Kunal Kamra on why his standup comedy is edgy, funny but completely safe\". The Indian Express. Retrieved 27 May 2018.|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321044721/https://indianexpress.com/article/express-sunday-eye/dont-get-mad-get-funny-5093304/|archive-date=21 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 1st March 2017, he released a comedy video titled \"Patriotism and the Government\" on [[YouTube]] mocking demonetization, government and the attitude of Indians towards the army.<ref name=\":1\" /> He received several death threats for uploading the video.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stand-up comedian Kunal Kamra receives death threats for his sketch on patriotism- Entertainment News, Firstpost |url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/stand-up-comedian-kunal-kamra-receives-death-threats-for-his-sketch-on-patriotism-3337986.html |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=Firstpost |date=16 March 2017 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320142304/http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/stand-up-comedian-kunal-kamra-receives-death-threats-for-his-sketch-on-patriotism-3337986.html |archive-date=20 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, he shared that he was asked by his landlady to vacate the premise due to \"political issues\".<ref name=\"vacate house\">{{cite news |title=Kunal Kamra asked to vacate his house: 'As a comedian having a political opinion comes at a cost'- Entertainment News, Firstpost |url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kunal-kamra-asked-to-vacate-his-house-as-a-comedian-having-a-political-opinion-comes-at-a-cost-4319567.html |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=Firstpost |date=25 January 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331013041/http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kunal-kamra-asked-to-vacate-his-house-as-a-comedian-having-a-political-opinion-comes-at-a-cost-4319567.html |archive-date=31 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Incident on Indigo flight==\nOn 28 January, Kamra, while travelling on an [[IndiGo]] flight, he heckled the news anchor [[Arnab Goswami]], inviting him to debate with him. Kamra had raised questions about Arnab's coverage of issues on national affairs and the [[suicide of Rohith Vemula]].<ref name=\"gulf\" /> Kamra later released a 1.51-minute long video of the incident on Twitter, which showed a non responsive Arnab while being questioned by Kamra.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kunal Kamra barred from flying Indigo, Air India |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kunal-kamra-barred-from-flying-indigo-for-6-months/article30677306.ece |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=28 January 2020 |language=en-IN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130164858/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kunal-kamra-barred-from-flying-indigo-for-6-months/article30677306.ece |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=SpiceJet bans Kunal Kamra, Twitter reminds the airline of Pragya Thakur incident |url=https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/news/india/spicejet-bans-kunal-kamra-twitter-reminds-the-airline-of-pragya-thakur-incident/articleshow/73726660.cms |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=Bangalore Mirror |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205152431/https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/news/india/spicejet-bans-kunal-kamra-twitter-reminds-the-airline-of-pragya-thakur-incident/articleshow/73726660.cms |archive-date=5 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Arnab did not ask the airline crew to intervene nor did he file a formal complaint over the incident, however the next day, Indigo banned Kamra from boarding its flight for a period of six months.<ref name=\"Lawsuit\" /> \n\nThe same day, a government owned airlines, [[Air India]], banned him indefinitely. Indian aviation minister, [[Hardeep Singh Puri]], tweeted that other airlines should follow suit and ban Kamra to ensure that an example was set.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/is-kunal-kamra-right-in-seeking-damages-from-indigo-for-flying-ban-heres-what-experts-say/articleshow/73863451.cms|title=Is Kunal Kamra right in seeking damages from IndiGo for flying ban? Here's what experts say|last=Chowdhury|first=Anirban|date=2020-02-02|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref><ref name=\"pilot\" /> Next day, low cost airlines [[SpiceJet]] and [[GoAir]] also banned him indefinitely. AirAsia and Vistara have not banned him yet and stated that they will wait for a written directive issued by the government before taking any action. The ban was criticized for being excessive for the incident and against the existing rules of DGCA.<ref name=\"ET Ban\">{{cite news |last1=Mishra |first1=Mihir |last2=Chowdhury |first2=Anirban |title=And the joke\u2019s on\u2026 Kunal Kamra flight bans |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/arnab-heckling-incident-after-indigo-air-india-spicejet-suspends-kunal-kamra/articleshow/73726336.cms |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=31 January 2020}}</ref> The pilot of the flight in which the incident occurred, later in an internal email, stated that Kamra was not unruly and expressed disappointment that IndiGo took action without consulting with the pilot-in-command.<ref name=\"pilot\">{{cite news |last1=Chandra |first1=Jagriti |title=Kunal Kamra was not unruly, says IndiGo pilot who flew the comedian |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kunal-kamra-was-not-unruly-says-indigo-pilot-who-flew-the-comedian/article30693719.ece |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=30 January 2020 |language=en-IN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201043648/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kunal-kamra-was-not-unruly-says-indigo-pilot-who-flew-the-comedian/article30693719.ece |archive-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFilm maker [[Anurag Kashyap]] refused to fly in the [[IndiGo]] airlines due to their decision to ban Kamra.<ref name=\"gulf\">{{cite news |title=Anurag Kashyap refuses to fly IndiGo to support comedian Kunal Kamra |url=https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/anurag-kashyap-refuses-to-fly-indigo-to-support-comedian-kunal-kamra-1.1580823452362 |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=gulfnews.com |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204230130/https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/anurag-kashyap-refuses-to-fly-indigo-to-support-comedian-kunal-kamra-1.1580823452362 |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two passengers of [[IndiGo]] also protested and displayed placards in the plane, in support of Kamra.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=Scroll |title=Watch: Passengers onboard an IndiGo flight protest against flying ban on comedian Kunal Kamra |url=https://scroll.in/video/952445/watch-passengers-onboard-an-indigo-flight-protest-against-flying-ban-on-comedian-kunal-kamra |accessdate=7 February 2020 |work=Scroll.in}}</ref>\n\nKamra has issued a legal notice to IndiGo against the travel ban demanding a compensation of {{INRConvert|25|l}}.<ref name=\"Lawsuit\">{{cite news |last1=NETWORK |first1=LIVELAW NEWS |title=Kunal Kamra Issues Legal Notice To Indigo Airlines Against Travel Ban; Demands Rs. 25L Compensation [Read Notice] |url=https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/kunal-kamra-issues-legal-notice-to-indigo-airlines-152242 |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=www.livelaw.in |date=1 February 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205153819/https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/kunal-kamra-issues-legal-notice-to-indigo-airlines-152242 |archive-date=5 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Kamra stated that a legal firm had taken up his case as a special case.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kamra |first1=Kunal |title=You\u2019re love & support is helping me go legal against @IndiGo6EAlso Lawmen & White have taken this fight to court for me as special case,To all artists out there don\u2019t fear there are enough good people in society to always support the constitution...https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/kunal-kamra-issues-legal-notice-to-indigo-airlines-152242\u00a0\u2026 |url=https://twitter.com/kunalkamra88/status/1223508796472987648 |website=@kunalkamra88 |accessdate=5 February 2020 |language=en |date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202184707/https://twitter.com/kunalkamra88/status/1223508796472987648 |archive-date=2 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== ''Shut Up Ya Kunal'' ==\n\nIn 2017, Kunal launched a YouTube podcast titled ''Shut Up Ya Kunal'' along with his friend Ramit Verma. The show features Kamra engaged in an informal discussion with politicians and activists from both ends of the spectrum.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1609531/youtuber-kunal-kamra-on-india-election-2019-modis-bjp-congress/|title=Ultra right-wing versus ultra spineless\u2014Kunal Kamra sums up Indian politics in 2019|last=Merelli|first=Annalisa|website=Quartz India|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101100417/https://qz.com/india/1609531/youtuber-kunal-kamra-on-india-election-2019-modis-bjp-congress/|archive-date=2019-11-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/magazine/845671/a-new-indian-comedy-podcast-is-finally-making-politicians-laugh-how-many-will-say-shut-up-ya-kunal|title=A new Indian comedy podcast is finally making politicians laugh. How many will say Shut Up Ya Kunal?|last=Rao|first=Soumya|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321050315/https://scroll.in/magazine/845671/a-new-indian-comedy-podcast-is-finally-making-politicians-laugh-how-many-will-say-shut-up-ya-kunal|archive-date=2019-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://eventseeker.com/artist/88699-kunal-kamra|title=Kunal Kamra - Artist Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=eventseeker.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> The videos are interspersed with news clips of the guests contradicting their own statements to comic effect.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Ramit Verma of the satirical Facebook page PeeingHuman is the show's creative director and editor.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadant.co/interview-kunal-kamra-political-comedy-potential-limitations/|title=\u2018Nobody Buys a Ticket to Put You on a Pedestal of Wokeness\u2019: Kunal Kamra, on the Potential & Limitations of Political Comedy in India|date=2019-05-22|website=Dead Ant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadant.co/modi-goswami-done-more-damage-to-the-media-than-anyone-could-ever-do-peeinghuman-creator/|title=Modi & Goswami 'Have Done More Damage To Indian Media Than Anyone': PeeingHuman Creator Ramit Verma|date=2019-02-18|website=Dead Ant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020093218/https://deadant.co/modi-goswami-done-more-damage-to-the-media-than-anyone-could-ever-do-peeinghuman-creator/|archive-date=2019-10-20|url-status=live}}</ref> The first episode aired on July 20, 2017 and featured [[Madhukeshwar Desai]], vice-president of the Bharatiya Janata Party\u2019s youth wing.<ref name=\":4\" /> The episode featuring the JNU Students Kanhaiya Kumar and Umar Khalid reached around a million views within hours of release. \n\nApart from his show, Kamra also performs live.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://eventseeker.com/artist/88699-kunal-kamra|title=Kunal Kamra - Artist Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=eventseeker.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+List of ''Shut Up Ya Kunal'' Episodes\n!No.\n!Guests\n|-\n|1\n|[[Madhukeshwar Desai]], (Vice-president of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP Youth Wing]])\n|-\n|2\n|[[Priyanka Chaturvedi]], (ex National Spokesperson, [[Indian National Congress|Congress]])\n|-\n|3\n|[[Kanhaiya Kumar]] and [[Umar Khalid]] ([[Jawaharlal Nehru University|JNU]] students)\n|-\n|4\n|[[Karuna Nundy]] (Supreme Court Lawyer) and [[Siddharth Varadarajan]] (Co-founder, [[The Wire (India)|The Wire]])\n|-\n|5\n|[[Shehla Rashid]] (ex Vice President, [[Jawaharlal Nehru University|JNU]]) and [[Jignesh Mevani]] ([[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]] [[Vadgam]], Gujarat)\n|-\n|6\n|[[Ravish Kumar]] ([[NDTV]]\n|-\n|7\n|[[Kavita Krishnan]], [[Politburo of the Communist Party of India (Marxist)|Politburo]] Member, [[Communist Party of India (Marxist\u2013Leninist) Liberation|CPI-ML]] and Secretary, All India Progressive Women's Association (AIPWA).\n|-\n|8\n|[[Ravish Kumar]] ([[NDTV]] Journalist) [Part 2]\n|-\n|9\n|[[Asaduddin Owaisi]], MP and President, [[All India Majlis-e-Ittehadul Muslimeen|All India Majlis-e-Ittehadul Muslimeen (AIMIM)]]\n|-\n|10\n|[[Atishi]] ([[Aam Aadmi Party]]) and Shweta Shalini ([[Bharatiya Janata Party]])\n|-\n|11\n|[[Javed Akhtar]] (poet, lyricist, and screenwriter) and [[Yogendra Yadav]] (politician, psephologist, and President of [[Swaraj India]])\n|-\n|12\n|[[Milind Deora]] (ex MP and President of [[Indian National Congress|Congress Mumbai]]) and [[Sachin Pilot]] (Deputy Chief Minister of [[Rajasthan]])\n|-\n|13\n|[[Arvind Kejriwal]] (CM, Delhi)\n|-\n|14\n|[[Javed Akhtar]] (poet, lyricist, and screenwriter) and [[Yogendra Yadav]] (politician, psephologist, and President of [[Swaraj India]]) (Part 2)\n|-\n|15\n|[[Anubhav Sinha]] (Director) and Anand Gandhi \n|-\n|16\n|[[Manish Sisodia]] (Deputy CM, Delhi) and Sanjay Singh (Rajyasabha MP) ([[Aam Aadmi Party]]) \n|-\n|17\n|[[Tejasvi Surya]] (MP, Bangalore South)<ref>{{Citation|title=Shut Up Ya Kunal - Episode 17 : Tejasvi Surya|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ea4GxJIJUjU|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Web series ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Name\n!Year\n!Genre\n!Channel\n!Notes\n|-\n|Canvas Laugh Club<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsbugz.com/kunal-kamra-wiki-biography-age-comedian-family-images/|title=Kunal Kamra shows|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321044725/https://www.newsbugz.com/kunal-kamra-wiki-biography-age-comedian-family-images/|archive-date=2019-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|2013\n|[[Comedy]]\n|[[STAR One|YouTube]]\n|\n|-\n|Shut up Ya Kunal<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://scroll.in/video/911515/watch-satirist-kunal-kamra-spoke-to-aap-and-bjp-representatives-for-30-minutes-and-nobody-shouted|title=Shut Ya Kunal - Ravish Kumar|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321050329/https://scroll.in/video/911515/watch-satirist-kunal-kamra-spoke-to-aap-and-bjp-representatives-for-30-minutes-and-nobody-shouted|archive-date=2019-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|2017\n|[[Podcast]]\n|[[YouTube]]\n|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{IMDb name|1555152}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Indian comedians]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox comedian\n|birth_name=Kunal Kamra\n|birth_date=3rd October 1988\n|nationality=Indian\n|notable_works=Shut up Ya Kunal, Fresh Thoughts\n|website=http://www.kunalkamra.in\n}}\n\n'''Kunal Kamra''' is a comedian who is recognised for his [[observational comedy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/fashion-and-trends/kunal-kamra-talks-about-his-chance-encounter-with-stand-up-comedy/story-cvCxtPNT1oss0Ta2SwISVL.html|title=Kunal Kamra chance encounter with stand up comedy|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321044724/https://www.hindustantimes.com/fashion-and-trends/kunal-kamra-talks-about-his-chance-encounter-with-stand-up-comedy/story-cvCxtPNT1oss0Ta2SwISVL.html|archive-date=2019-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, after an incident on [[IndiGo]] airlines where he confronted the Indian news anchor [[Arnab Goswami]], he was banned by five Indian Airlines.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/kunal-kamra-flight-ban-what-gets-you-on-a-no-fly-list/ban-on-comedian-kunal-kamra/slideshow/73759924.cms|title=Kunal Kamra flight ban: What gets you on a 'No-Fly' List}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nKunal Kamra was born on 3 October 1988, in [[Mahim]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/kunal-kamra-indian-comedian-riles-ruling-party-edgy-humour-180417065234329.html|title=Kunal Kamra birth place - Mahim|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321180823/https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/kunal-kamra-indian-comedian-riles-ruling-party-edgy-humour-180417065234329.html|archive-date=2019-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mumbai]], [[India]]. Kamra grew up in Mumbai, and joined [[Jai Hind College]] for a degree in [[commerce]]. He dropped in second year to start working as a production assistant in Prasoon Pandey\u2019s ad film production house Corcoise Films, where he stayed for eleven years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/kunal-kamra-on-his-shows-and-indian-stand-up-comedy/article19296076.ece|title=Murthy, Neeraja (2017-07-17). \"Bring your brains along\". The Hindu. Retrieved 22 May 2018.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015140436/https://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/kunal-kamra-on-his-shows-and-indian-stand-up-comedy/article19296076.ece|archive-date=15 October 2018|dead-url=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/C39AsWWaic7qvGsONZNCnJ/Kunal-Kamra-The-accidental-revolutionary.html|title=Kunal Kamra: The accidental revolutionary|last=Chatterjee|first=Suprateek|date=2018-03-16|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\nHe started performing as a standup comedian in 2013, with a gig at the Canvas Laugh Club in Mumbai.<ref name=\":2\" /> A clip of one of his gigs, uploaded on YouTube in 2017, lead to him receiving death threats for his satirical take on Indian hyper-nationalism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thequint.com/neon/shut-up-ya-kunal-kamra-comedian-political-review|title=\"Please Don't 'Shut Up Ya Kunal': Enjoying Politics Through Comedy\". The Quint. Retrieved 27 May 2018.|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015140428/https://www.thequint.com/neon/shut-up-ya-kunal-kamra-comedian-political-review|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He started his eponymous titled web-series ''Shut Up Ya Kunal'' in July 2017 along with Ramit Verma.<ref name=\":4\" /> The episodes typically feature a conversation with one or more invited guests, interposed with clips of news segments or debates, edited for humour.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/express-sunday-eye/dont-get-mad-get-funny-5093304/|title=D'souza, Dipti Nagpaul (11 March 2018). \"Don't Get Mad, Get Funny: Kunal Kamra on why his standup comedy is edgy, funny but completely safe\". The Indian Express. Retrieved 27 May 2018.|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321044721/https://indianexpress.com/article/express-sunday-eye/dont-get-mad-get-funny-5093304/|archive-date=21 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 1st March 2017, he released a comedy video titled \"Patriotism and the Government\" on [[YouTube]] mocking demonetization, government and the attitude of Indians towards the army.<ref name=\":1\" /> He received several death threats for uploading the video.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stand-up comedian Kunal Kamra receives death threats for his sketch on patriotism- Entertainment News, Firstpost |url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/stand-up-comedian-kunal-kamra-receives-death-threats-for-his-sketch-on-patriotism-3337986.html |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=Firstpost |date=16 March 2017 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320142304/http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/stand-up-comedian-kunal-kamra-receives-death-threats-for-his-sketch-on-patriotism-3337986.html |archive-date=20 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, he shared that he was asked by his landlady to vacate the premise due to \"political issues\".<ref name=\"vacate house\">{{cite news |title=Kunal Kamra asked to vacate his house: 'As a comedian having a political opinion comes at a cost'- Entertainment News, Firstpost |url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kunal-kamra-asked-to-vacate-his-house-as-a-comedian-having-a-political-opinion-comes-at-a-cost-4319567.html |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=Firstpost |date=25 January 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331013041/http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kunal-kamra-asked-to-vacate-his-house-as-a-comedian-having-a-political-opinion-comes-at-a-cost-4319567.html |archive-date=31 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Incident on Indigo flight==\nOn 28 January, Kamra, while travelling on an [[IndiGo]] flight, he heckled the news anchor [[Arnab Goswami]], inviting him to debate with him. Kamra had raised questions about Arnab's coverage of issues on national affairs and the [[suicide of Rohith Vemula]].<ref name=\"gulf\" /> Kamra later released a 1.51-minute long video of the incident on Twitter, which showed a non responsive Arnab while being questioned by Kamra.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kunal Kamra barred from flying Indigo, Air India |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kunal-kamra-barred-from-flying-indigo-for-6-months/article30677306.ece |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=28 January 2020 |language=en-IN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130164858/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kunal-kamra-barred-from-flying-indigo-for-6-months/article30677306.ece |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=SpiceJet bans Kunal Kamra, Twitter reminds the airline of Pragya Thakur incident |url=https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/news/india/spicejet-bans-kunal-kamra-twitter-reminds-the-airline-of-pragya-thakur-incident/articleshow/73726660.cms |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=Bangalore Mirror |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205152431/https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/news/india/spicejet-bans-kunal-kamra-twitter-reminds-the-airline-of-pragya-thakur-incident/articleshow/73726660.cms |archive-date=5 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Arnab did not ask the airline crew to intervene nor did he file a formal complaint over the incident, however the next day, Indigo banned Kamra from boarding its flight for a period of six months.<ref name=\"Lawsuit\" /> \n\nThe same day, a government owned airlines, [[Air India]], banned him indefinitely. Indian aviation minister, [[Hardeep Singh Puri]], tweeted that other airlines should follow suit and ban Kamra to ensure that an example was set.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/is-kunal-kamra-right-in-seeking-damages-from-indigo-for-flying-ban-heres-what-experts-say/articleshow/73863451.cms|title=Is Kunal Kamra right in seeking damages from IndiGo for flying ban? Here's what experts say|last=Chowdhury|first=Anirban|date=2020-02-02|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref><ref name=\"pilot\" /> Next day, low cost airlines [[SpiceJet]] and [[GoAir]] also banned him indefinitely. AirAsia and Vistara have not banned him yet and stated that they will wait for a written directive issued by the government before taking any action. The ban was criticized for being excessive for the incident and against the existing rules of DGCA.<ref name=\"ET Ban\">{{cite news |last1=Mishra |first1=Mihir |last2=Chowdhury |first2=Anirban |title=And the joke\u2019s on\u2026 Kunal Kamra flight bans |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/arnab-heckling-incident-after-indigo-air-india-spicejet-suspends-kunal-kamra/articleshow/73726336.cms |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=31 January 2020}}</ref> The pilot of the flight in which the incident occurred, later in an internal email, stated that Kamra was not unruly and expressed disappointment that IndiGo took action without consulting with the pilot-in-command.<ref name=\"pilot\">{{cite news |last1=Chandra |first1=Jagriti |title=Kunal Kamra was not unruly, says IndiGo pilot who flew the comedian |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kunal-kamra-was-not-unruly-says-indigo-pilot-who-flew-the-comedian/article30693719.ece |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=30 January 2020 |language=en-IN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201043648/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kunal-kamra-was-not-unruly-says-indigo-pilot-who-flew-the-comedian/article30693719.ece |archive-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFilm maker [[Anurag Kashyap]] refused to fly in the [[IndiGo]] airlines due to their decision to ban Kamra.<ref name=\"gulf\">{{cite news |title=Anurag Kashyap refuses to fly IndiGo to support comedian Kunal Kamra |url=https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/anurag-kashyap-refuses-to-fly-indigo-to-support-comedian-kunal-kamra-1.1580823452362 |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=gulfnews.com |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204230130/https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/anurag-kashyap-refuses-to-fly-indigo-to-support-comedian-kunal-kamra-1.1580823452362 |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two passengers of [[IndiGo]] also protested and displayed placards in the plane, in support of Kamra.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=Scroll |title=Watch: Passengers onboard an IndiGo flight protest against flying ban on comedian Kunal Kamra |url=https://scroll.in/video/952445/watch-passengers-onboard-an-indigo-flight-protest-against-flying-ban-on-comedian-kunal-kamra |accessdate=7 February 2020 |work=Scroll.in}}</ref>\n\nKamra has issued a legal notice to IndiGo against the travel ban demanding a compensation of {{INRConvert|25|l}}.<ref name=\"Lawsuit\">{{cite news |last1=NETWORK |first1=LIVELAW NEWS |title=Kunal Kamra Issues Legal Notice To Indigo Airlines Against Travel Ban; Demands Rs. 25L Compensation [Read Notice] |url=https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/kunal-kamra-issues-legal-notice-to-indigo-airlines-152242 |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=www.livelaw.in |date=1 February 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205153819/https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/kunal-kamra-issues-legal-notice-to-indigo-airlines-152242 |archive-date=5 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Kamra stated that a legal firm had taken up his case as a special case.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kamra |first1=Kunal |title=You\u2019re love & support is helping me go legal against @IndiGo6EAlso Lawmen & White have taken this fight to court for me as special case,To all artists out there don\u2019t fear there are enough good people in society to always support the constitution...https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/kunal-kamra-issues-legal-notice-to-indigo-airlines-152242\u00a0\u2026 |url=https://twitter.com/kunalkamra88/status/1223508796472987648 |website=@kunalkamra88 |accessdate=5 February 2020 |language=en |date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202184707/https://twitter.com/kunalkamra88/status/1223508796472987648 |archive-date=2 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== ''Shut Up Ya Kunal'' ==\n\nIn 2017, Kunal launched a YouTube podcast titled ''Shut Up Ya Kunal'' along with his friend Ramit Verma. The show features Kamra engaged in an informal discussion with politicians and activists from both ends of the spectrum.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1609531/youtuber-kunal-kamra-on-india-election-2019-modis-bjp-congress/|title=Ultra right-wing versus ultra spineless\u2014Kunal Kamra sums up Indian politics in 2019|last=Merelli|first=Annalisa|website=Quartz India|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101100417/https://qz.com/india/1609531/youtuber-kunal-kamra-on-india-election-2019-modis-bjp-congress/|archive-date=2019-11-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/magazine/845671/a-new-indian-comedy-podcast-is-finally-making-politicians-laugh-how-many-will-say-shut-up-ya-kunal|title=A new Indian comedy podcast is finally making politicians laugh. How many will say Shut Up Ya Kunal?|last=Rao|first=Soumya|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321050315/https://scroll.in/magazine/845671/a-new-indian-comedy-podcast-is-finally-making-politicians-laugh-how-many-will-say-shut-up-ya-kunal|archive-date=2019-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://eventseeker.com/artist/88699-kunal-kamra|title=Kunal Kamra - Artist Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=eventseeker.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> The videos are interspersed with news clips of the guests contradicting their own statements to comic effect.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Ramit Verma of the satirical Facebook page PeeingHuman is the show's creative director and editor.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadant.co/interview-kunal-kamra-political-comedy-potential-limitations/|title=\u2018Nobody Buys a Ticket to Put You on a Pedestal of Wokeness\u2019: Kunal Kamra, on the Potential & Limitations of Political Comedy in India|date=2019-05-22|website=Dead Ant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadant.co/modi-goswami-done-more-damage-to-the-media-than-anyone-could-ever-do-peeinghuman-creator/|title=Modi & Goswami 'Have Done More Damage To Indian Media Than Anyone': PeeingHuman Creator Ramit Verma|date=2019-02-18|website=Dead Ant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020093218/https://deadant.co/modi-goswami-done-more-damage-to-the-media-than-anyone-could-ever-do-peeinghuman-creator/|archive-date=2019-10-20|url-status=live}}</ref> The first episode aired on July 20, 2017 and featured [[Madhukeshwar Desai]], vice-president of the Bharatiya Janata Party\u2019s youth wing.<ref name=\":4\" /> The episode featuring the JNU Students Kanhaiya Kumar and Umar Khalid reached around a million views within hours of release. \n\nApart from his show, Kamra also performs live.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://eventseeker.com/artist/88699-kunal-kamra|title=Kunal Kamra - Artist Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=eventseeker.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+List of ''Shut Up Ya Kunal'' Episodes\n!No.\n!Guests\n|-\n|1\n|[[Madhukeshwar Desai]], (Vice-president of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP Youth Wing]])\n|-\n|2\n|[[Priyanka Chaturvedi]], (ex National Spokesperson, [[Indian National Congress|Congress]])\n|-\n|3\n|[[Kanhaiya Kumar]] and [[Umar Khalid]] ([[Jawaharlal Nehru University|JNU]] students)\n|-\n|4\n|[[Karuna Nundy]] (Supreme Court Lawyer) and [[Siddharth Varadarajan]] (Co-founder, [[The Wire (India)|The Wire]])\n|-\n|5\n|[[Shehla Rashid]] (ex Vice President, [[Jawaharlal Nehru University|JNU]]) and [[Jignesh Mevani]] ([[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]] [[Vadgam]], Gujarat)\n|-\n|6\n|[[Ravish Kumar]] ([[NDTV]]\n|-\n|7\n|[[Kavita Krishnan]], [[Politburo of the Communist Party of India (Marxist)|Politburo]] Member, [[Communist Party of India (Marxist\u2013Leninist) Liberation|CPI-ML]] and Secretary, All India Progressive Women's Association (AIPWA).\n|-\n|8\n|[[Ravish Kumar]] ([[NDTV]] Journalist) [Part 2]\n|-\n|9\n|[[Asaduddin Owaisi]], MP and President, [[All India Majlis-e-Ittehadul Muslimeen|All India Majlis-e-Ittehadul Muslimeen (AIMIM)]]\n|-\n|10\n|[[Atishi]] ([[Aam Aadmi Party]]) and Shweta Shalini ([[Bharatiya Janata Party]])\n|-\n|11\n|[[Javed Akhtar]] (poet, lyricist, and screenwriter) and [[Yogendra Yadav]] (politician, psephologist, and President of [[Swaraj India]])\n|-\n|12\n|[[Milind Deora]] (ex MP and President of [[Indian National Congress|Congress Mumbai]]) and [[Sachin Pilot]] (Deputy Chief Minister of [[Rajasthan]])\n|-\n|13\n|[[Arvind Kejriwal]] (CM, Delhi)\n|-\n|14\n|[[Javed Akhtar]] (poet, lyricist, and screenwriter) and [[Yogendra Yadav]] (politician, psephologist, and President of [[Swaraj India]]) (Part 2)\n|-\n|15\n|[[Anubhav Sinha]] (Director) and Anand Gandhi \n|-\n|16\n|[[Manish Sisodia]] (Deputy CM, Delhi) and Sanjay Singh (Rajyasabha MP) ([[Aam Aadmi Party]]) \n|-\n|17\n|[[Tejasvi Surya]] (MP, Bangalore South)<ref>{{Citation|title=Shut Up Ya Kunal - Episode 17 : Tejasvi Surya|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ea4GxJIJUjU|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Web series ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Name\n!Year\n!Genre\n!Channel\n!Notes\n|-\n|Canvas Laugh Club<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsbugz.com/kunal-kamra-wiki-biography-age-comedian-family-images/|title=Kunal Kamra shows|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321044725/https://www.newsbugz.com/kunal-kamra-wiki-biography-age-comedian-family-images/|archive-date=2019-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|2013\n|[[Comedy]]\n|[[STAR One|YouTube]]\n|\n|-\n|Shut up Ya Kunal<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://scroll.in/video/911515/watch-satirist-kunal-kamra-spoke-to-aap-and-bjp-representatives-for-30-minutes-and-nobody-shouted|title=Shut Ya Kunal - Ravish Kumar|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321050329/https://scroll.in/video/911515/watch-satirist-kunal-kamra-spoke-to-aap-and-bjp-representatives-for-30-minutes-and-nobody-shouted|archive-date=2019-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|2017\n|[[Podcast]]\n|[[YouTube]]\n|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{IMDb name|1555152}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Indian comedians]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "DEBMALYA1991", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIncident on Indigo flight", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kunal_Kamra"}
{"title_page": "Bill Hader", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor, comedian, writer, and producer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Bill Hader\n| image        = [[https://www.refinery29.com/images/9085048.jpg]]\n| image_size   = 200px\n| caption      = Hader in September 2016\n| birth_name   = William Thomas Hader Jr.\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1978|6|7}}\n| birth_place  = [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| occupation   = {{flatlist|\n*Actor\n*comedian\n*writer\n*producer\n*director\n}}\n| years_active = 1999\u2013present\n| alma_mater   = [[Scottsdale Community College]]\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Maggie Carey]]|2006|2018|reason=div}}\n| children      = Hannah Hader<br>Harper Hader<br>Hayley Hader}}\n'''William Thomas Hader Jr.''' (born June 7, 1978)<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/bill-hader-57635941/| work= [[Hollywood.com]] | title=Bill Hader {{!}} Biography and Filmography {{!}} 1978| accessdate= May 5, 2017}}</ref> is an American actor, comedian, writer, producer, and director. He rose to fame as a cast member on the [[NBC]] variety series ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (2005\u20132013) for which he received four [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations and a  [[Peabody Award]].\n\nHader has had supporting roles in the films ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' (2007), ''[[Tropic Thunder]]'' (2008), ''[[Forgetting Sarah Marshall]]'' (2008), ''[[Night at the Museum: Battle of the Smithsonian]]'' (2009), ''[[Paul (film)|Paul]]'' (2011), ''[[Men in Black 3]]'' (2012) and leading roles in ''[[The Skeleton Twins]]'' (2014), ''[[Trainwreck (film)|Trainwreck]]'' (2015) and ''[[It Chapter Two]]'' (2019) as an adult [[Richie Tozier]]. He has voiced lead characters in the  ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (franchise)|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs]]'' franchise (2009\u20132014), ''[[Inside Out (2015 film)|Inside Out]]'' (2015), the ''[[The Angry Birds Movie|Angry Birds]]'' films (2016, 2019), ''[[Sausage Party]]'' (2016), ''[[Ralph Breaks the Internet]]'' (2018) and supporting roles in ''[[Turbo (2013 film)|Turbo]]'' (2013), ''[[Monsters University]]'' (2013) and ''[[Finding Dory]]'' (2016).\n\nDuring his time on ''Saturday Night Live'', Hader became known for his impressions and his character [[Stefon]] in the ''[[Weekend Update]]'' segments. He is the co-creator, writer, and producer of the [[IFC (U.S. TV channel)|IFC]] mockumentary comedy series ''[[Documentary Now!]]'' (2015\u2013present), in which he stars alongside [[Fred Armisen]]. In 2018, Hader created and began starring as the titular assassin in the [[HBO]] dark comedy series ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]'', which earned him two Emmy Awards for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]] and consecutive nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]] for its first two seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/2018-emmy-nominations-list-all-nominees-1202425072/|title=Emmy Nominations: 'Game Of Thrones' Tops Noms, With Netflix & HBO Leading Way \u2013 Full List|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=July 12, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=October 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHader was born and raised in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], the son of Sherri Renee (n\u00e9e Patton) and William Thomas Hader.<ref name=fdnr1>''[[Finding Your Roots]]'', January 26, 2016, PBS</ref><ref name=dla>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Michael |title=Hader about to be a proud papa|newspaper=Tulsa World|date=September 18, 2009|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/site/printerfriendlystory.aspx?articleid=20090918_283_D1_BillHa114485|accessdate=November 15, 2010}}</ref> His father owned an air-freight company and worked as a restaurant manager, truck driver and occasional [[stand-up comedian]];<ref name=\"nyt2007\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/23/movies/23itzk.html?_r=0 |title=A 'Superbad' Geek's Progress |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 23, 2007 |first=Dave |last=Itzkoff |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref> his mother was a dance teacher.<ref name=\"rollingstone2014\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/features/bill-hader-trades-stefon-for-serious-drama-in-the-skeleton-twins-20140911 |title=Bill Hader Trades Stefon for Serious Drama in 'The Skeleton Twins' |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=September 11, 2014 |first=Jonah |last=Weiner |accessdate=October 13, 2014 }}</ref> He has two younger sisters, Katie and Kara.<ref name=dla/> His surname originates in Germany; his ancestry includes German, Danish, Irish, and English.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/weta/finding-your-roots/blog/bill-haders-interactive-family-tree/ |title=Bill Hader's Interactive Family Tree &#124; Finding Your Roots |publisher=PBS |date=2016-01-28 |accessdate=2016-12-21}}</ref><ref>https://www.businessinsider.com/pbs-finding-your-roots-bill-hader-2016-1?IR=T</ref>\n\nHader attended Patrick Henry Elementary School, [[Edison Preparatory School|Edison Junior High]], and [[Cascia Hall Preparatory School]].<ref>Michael Smith, [http://www.tulsaworld.com/entertainment/spot/article.aspx?articleID=070817_8_ES14_Itwas70410 \"Super Glad: Native Tulsan Bill Hader moves from 'SNL' success to big-budget film roles,\"] ''[[Tulsa World]]'', August 17, 2007.</ref><ref>Michael Smith, [http://www.tulsaworld.com/spot/article.aspx?subjectid=243&articleid=20090403_282_D1_JasonP931046 \"Talking about Tulsa days: Bill Hader finally found a vocation in comedy\"], ''[[Tulsa World]]'', April 3, 2009.</ref> He had \"a hard time focusing on class\" and was always \"joking around\". Though he was not hated by classmates, he felt he never truly fit in and filled his time watching movies and reading.<ref name=\"pb13\"/> He appreciated [[Monty Python]], [[British comedy]], and the films of [[Mel Brooks]] and [[Woody Allen]],<ref name=\"i14\">{{cite news|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/bill-hader#_|title=Interview: Bill Hader|author=[[Danny McBride]]|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|accessdate=November 26, 2015}}</ref> many of which he was introduced to through his father.<ref name=\"pb13\"/> He made short films with friends and starred in a school production of ''[[The Glass Menagerie]]''.<ref name=\"i14\"/>\n\nHe was unable to gain admission to top [[film school]]s because of his \"abysmal\" grades, so he instead enrolled at [[The Art Institute of Phoenix]],<ref name=\"07ok\">Gene Triplett, [http://newsok.com/article/3105814 \"Funny things about Bill Hader: Growing up in Tulsa as 'movie nerd' gave comic actor material,\"] ''[[The Oklahoman]]'', August 17, 2007.</ref> and later [[Scottsdale Community College]].<ref name=\"pb13\"/> Hader has mentioned that his very first job was selling Christmas trees. He also worked as an usher at a movie theater in nearby [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]], which allowed him to see films for free. He was fired for [[Spoiler (media)|spoiling]] the ending of the 1997 film ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' to noisy patrons.<ref name=\"huffpost07-14\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/07/13/bill-hader-mike-sacks-interview-poking-a-dead-frog-_n_5582142.html |title=Bill Hader Got Fired For Spoiling The End Of 'Titanic' & 10 More Facts You Didn't Know |work=The Huffington Post |date=July 14, 2014 |first=Katla |last=McGlynn |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"ifc14\"/> At Scottsdale, he met Nicholas Jasenovec, the director of ''[[Paper Heart (film)|Paper Heart]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/watch-extensive-2-1-2-hour-talk-with-bill-hader-about-his-career-films-and-more-20140813 |title=Watch: Extensive 2 1/2 Hour Talk With Bill Hader About His Career, Films And More |work=Indie Wire |date=August 13, 2014 |first=Tess |last=Hoffman |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1999\u20132004: Early career===\nHader's aspirations of becoming a filmmaker<ref name=\"huffpost07-14\"/> eventually led him to drop out of college and move to Los Angeles in 1999.<ref name=\"nyt2007\"/><ref name=\"pb13\">{{cite news|title=20Q: Bill Hader|work=[[Playboy]]|author=Rob Tannenbaum|date=September 2013|url=http://playboy.co.za/20q-bill-hader|accessdate=November 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126175804/http://playboy.co.za/20q-bill-hader|archive-date=November 26, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> His parents were supportive of his decision to move, and Hader used the money they had originally saved for his college education to cover his living expenses when he arrived in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"i14\"/> He found work as a [[production assistant]] (PA) while scouring the back pages of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'',<ref name=\"g14\"/> and he hoped to advance far enough to become an assistant director.<ref name=\"g14\"/> He spent much of his young adulthood \"lonely and underemployed,\" filling large amounts of spare time with movie marathons.<ref name=\"g14\">{{cite news|title=Bill Hader's Day Off|author=Amos Barhsad|publisher=[[Grantland.com]]|date=August 25, 2014|url=http://grantland.com/features/bill-hader-saturday-night-live-snl-week/|accessdate=November 26, 2015}}</ref> He regularly worked 18-hour days as a PA, having little time to pursue his creative ambitions.<ref name=\"i14\"/> He worked as a PA on the DVD ''[[Empire of Dreams: The Story of the Star Wars Trilogy]]''; the feature films ''[[James Dean (film)|James Dean]]'',<ref name=\"jamesfrancoesquire\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.esquire.com/features/james-franco/james-franco-bill-hader-0910 |title=Four Introductions to James Franco |magazine=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |first=Bill |last=Hader |date=August 11, 2010 |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref> ''[[Spider-Man (2002 film)|Spider-Man]]'',<ref name=\"jamesfrancoesquire\"/> and ''[[Collateral Damage (film)|Collateral Damage]]'';<ref name=\"nyt2007\"/> as well as a post-production assistant on [[VH1]] television's ''[[The Surreal Life]]''.<ref name=\"huffpost2010\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aoltv.com/2010/09/24/snl-star-bill-hader-talks-the-new-season-jon-hamms-return-an/ |title='SNL' Star Bill Hader Talks the New Season, Jon Hamm's Return and His 'Surreal Life' Experience with Corey Feldman |work=The Huffington Post |date=September 24, 2010 |first=Kim |last=Potts |accessdate=October 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921063946/http://www.aoltv.com/2010/09/24/snl-star-bill-hader-talks-the-new-season-jon-hamms-return-an/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Hader briefly worked as a PA and stage manager on [[Playboy TV]]'s ''[[Night Calls]]'';<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifc.com/fix/2014/09/bill-hader-playboy-tv-kimmel |title=BILL HADER TALKS ABOUT HIS PLAYBOY TV PAST ON KIMMEL |publisher=IFC |date=September 10, 2014 |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/tv/2014/09/bill-hader-jimmy-kimmel-playboy-call-in-show/ |title=Here's Bill Hader Describing What It Was Like To Work The Phones for a Playboy Call-In Sex Show |publisher=Uproxx |date=September 10, 2014 |first=Kris |last=Maske |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"nyobserver2014\">{{cite news|url=http://observer.com/2014/09/funnyman-bill-hader-on-going-serious-you-have-to-empty-yourself-a-little-bit/ |title=Funnyman Bill Hader on Going Serious: 'You Have to Empty Yourself a Little Bit' |newspaper=New York Observer |date=September 11, 2014 |first=Vinnie |last=Mancuso |accessdate=October 22, 2014 }}</ref> but quit, as he feared it would disappoint his parents.<ref name=\"ifc14\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ifc.com/shows/documentary-now/blog/2015/08/the-many-weird-jobs-of-bill-hader|title=5 Jobs You Probably Didn't Know Bill Hader Once Had|author=Steele|first=Brian|date=August 24, 2015|website=|publisher=[[IFC (TV channel)|IFC.com]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref> He eventually quit being a PA altogether after a bad experience shooting ''[[The Scorpion King]]''.<ref name=\"g14\"/>\n\nHader subsequently secured a job working as a nighttime assistant editor at post-production facility [[Triage Entertainment]].<ref name=\"i14\"/><ref name=\"g14\"/> He invested money into his own short film, but was too embarrassed to release it. Shortly thereafter, Hader and his then-longtime girlfriend broke up.<ref name=\"fcc14\">{{cite news|title=How Bill Hader Went from Production Assistant to ''SNL'' Hero to Leading Man|author=Joe Berkowitz|date=September 24, 2014|work=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]|url=http://www.fastcocreate.com/3036180/then-and-now/how-bill-hader-went-from-production-assistant-to-snl-hero-to-leading-man|accessdate=November 26, 2015}}</ref> Desperate for a change, he began attending comedy classes with friends at [[improvisational comedy]] enterprise [[the Second City]] in March 2003.<ref name=\"07ok\"/> He quickly realized that comedy was the creative outlet that he had needed since he made the decision to leave higher education behind,<ref name=\"i14\"/> and soon Hader, his new compatriot in comedy Matt Offerman, and their two friends and fellow humor enthusiasts Eric Filipkowski and Mel Cowan, elected to form their own sketch comedy group.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hollywoodphony.wordpress.com/2008/05/11/my-father-jocko-filipkowski/|title=My father, Jocko Filipkowski|date=2008-05-11|work=hollywoodphony|access-date=2018-04-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Christening their group ''Animals from the Future'', the four frequently appeared to small audiences at backyard shows in Van Nuys.<ref name=\"g14\"/> Matt's brother, actor [[Nick Offerman]], told his wife, [[Megan Mullally]], about the group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/08/22/159766489/bill-hader-on-sketch-comedy-his-love-of-old-films |title=Bill Hader on Sketch Comedy, His Love of Old Films |publisher=NPR |date=August 22, 2012 |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theringer.com/tv/2018/3/19/17131052/bill-hader-barry-show-hbo|title=The Name's Hader \u2026 Bill Hader|work=The Ringer|access-date=2018-04-20}}</ref> After attending one of the group's backyard appearances, Mullally told Hader of her intention to discuss him with [[Lorne Michaels]] of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (''SNL''). As a result of Mullally's recommendation, Hader was asked to audition for the show and he soon flew to New York to audition for a group of ''SNL'' producers. Hader had no impressions prepared when he was invited to audition. He was nervous and struggled to display his strengths during the audition. This resulted in his spontaneous imitation of an elderly Italian man he had once overheard. The impression would later become the first of Hader's many recurring characters on the show: Vinny Vedecci.<ref name=\"g14\" /> As a result of the audition, Hader got an agent and manager.<ref name=\"pb13\"/> Just before he was officially invited to begin work on ''SNL'', Hader was working as an assistant editor on ''[[Iron Chef America]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gawker.com/5784918/bill-hader-shares-his-road-to-saturday-night-live |title=Bill Hader Shares His Road to Saturday Night Live |author=Whitney Jefferson |publisher=Gawker Media |work=Gawker |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115013528/http://gawker.com/5784918/bill-hader-shares-his-road-to-saturday-night-live |archivedate=January 15, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n===2005\u20132013: Breakthrough and ''Saturday Night Live''===\nHader was hired as a featured player and made his debut on the show on October 1, 2005. His first role was as a [[psychologist]] giving his views about life and death during the emergency landing of [[JetBlue Airways Flight 292]]. He felt he had gone from \"preschool to [[Harvard]].\"<ref name=\"fcc14\"/> He became the \"impressions guy,\" hoping to fill a utility-player role \"like his hero [[Phil Hartman]]\".<ref name=\"g14\"/> Hader has said that he performed impersonations of teachers and friends when he was growing up but did not do impersonations of famous people until his ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' audition.<ref>[http://billhaderonline.com/main/2007/10/08/bill-hader-does-interview-with-bill-hader-online \"Bill Hader does interview with BHO!\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009113151/http://billhaderonline.com/main/2007/10/08/bill-hader-does-interview-with-bill-hader-online/ |date=October 9, 2011 }}. Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref> His list of impressions includes [[Vincent Price]] in the Variety Vault sketches, [[Keith Morrison]], [[Harvey Fierstein]], [[Al Pacino]], [[Rick Perry]], [[John Malkovich]], [[James Carville]], [[Julian Assange]], [[Eliot Spitzer]], [[Alan Alda]], [[Clint Eastwood]], and [[Charlie Sheen]]. On July 19, 2012, Hader received his first nomination for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series]] for his work on ''SNL''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/emmys-2012-saturday-night-live-bill-hader-351992|title=Emmys 2012: 'SNL's' Bill Hader Shocked By Nomination, Says It Wasn't on His Radar|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=July 19, 2012|first=Philiana|last=Ng|date=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/19/emmy-nominees-bill-hader-of-saturday-night-live/ | work=The New York Times | first=Dave | last=Itzkoff | title=Emmy Nominees: Bill Hader of 'Saturday Night Live' | date=July 19, 2012}}</ref> He is the first male ''SNL'' cast member to receive this nomination since Eddie Murphy in 1984.\n\nDespite this, Hader suffered from anxiety and sleep problems during his tenure at the program.<ref name=\"pb13\"/> He never felt \"truly comfortable\" throughout his first four seasons.<ref name=\"g14\"/> He was insecure that he had less comedy experience than his peers. He would often not sleep on Fridays before the show, and would feel light-headed prior to broadcasts.<ref name=\"pb13\"/> He was neurotic regarding his performances; Hader called his early performances \"rigid\".<ref name=\"g14\"/> On one occasion, he began having a [[panic attack]], live on air, while impersonating Julian Assange. It was the final episode of 2010 (hosted by [[Jeff Bridges]]), and Hader remembered; \"It felt like someone was sitting on my chest. I couldn't breathe, I started sweating. I thought, ''This is not good \u2014 abort! abort!''\"<ref name=\"pb13\"/> Hader is also prone to [[Migraine|migraines,]] and also suffered one live on air; [[Jason Sudeikis]] had to guide him on and offstage as he couldn't see anything.<ref>{{Citation|last=Paul Ofcharsky|title=Bill Hader's Migraines|date=2018-03-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gPzcmsBMDL0&t=1m39s|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref> Lorne Michaels tried to put him at ease by remarking to him, \"You can work here as long as you want,\" after the incident.<ref name=\"g14\"/>\n\nAmong the characters Hader played was [[Stefon]], ''[[Weekend Update]]''{{'}}s flamboyant New York City correspondent, whose recommendations consist solely of bizarre nightclubs involving nightmarish characters. Stefon is in love with and married to [[Seth Meyers]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jue|first1=Teresa|title=Bill Hader discusses the origins of Stefon on 'Seth Meyers'|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/09/16/bill-hader-discusses-the-origins-of-stefon-on-late-night-with-seth-meyers|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=August 2, 2016|date=September 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Busis|first1=Hillary|title='Saturday Night Live': A full directory of Stefon's favorite clubs. (This post has EVERYTHING.)|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2013/05/17/saturday-night-live-stefon-clubs-everything|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=August 2, 2016|date=May 17, 2013}}</ref> He was originally a one-shot character on a season-34 sketch where a screenwriter named David Zolesky (played by [[Ben Affleck]]) invites his estranged brother Stefon over to pitch a family-friendly sports drama about a college student who bonds with his grandfather so he can try out for the college football team.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Franks|first1=Jonathan|title=Stefon Flashback: In His SNL Debut with Ben Affleck, He Was Just Plain Scary!|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/1536610/stefon-flashback-snl-debut/|website=[[Inquisitr]]|accessdate=August 2, 2016|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> He is based on two people ''SNL'' writer [[John Mulaney]] and Hader met: a wannabe club owner who always invited Mulaney to weird underground clubs and a barista Hader met who looks, speaks, and dresses like Stefon.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dalton|first1=Christine|title=John Mulaney Reveals The Story Behind Stefon On 'Late Night'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/04/john-mulaney-stefon-late-night_n_5092351.html|website=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=August 2, 2016|date=April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter his film debut ''[[You, Me and Dupree]]'' (2006), Hader had a wide range of roles in 2007, such as [[Katherine Heigl]]'s character's editor at [[E!]] in ''[[Knocked Up]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kirk|first1=Jeremy|title=35 Things We Learned From the 'Knocked Up' Commentary|url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/35-things-we-learned-from-the-knocked-up-commentary-f2a65c8e511c|website=Film School Rejects|accessdate=August 3, 2016|date=October 6, 2011}}</ref> the acid-taking mechanic Dave in ''[[Hot Rod (2007 film)|Hot Rod]]'' alongside'' SNL'' castmate [[Andy Samberg]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Edwin|title=A Definitive Ranking of the 11 Funniest Hot Rod Scenes|url=https://www.beamly.com/tv-film/definitive-ranking-11-funniest-hot-rod-scenes|publisher=[[Beamly]]|accessdate=August 3, 2016|date=September 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612015717/https://www.beamly.com/tv-film/definitive-ranking-11-funniest-hot-rod-scenes|archive-date=June 12, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> a recumbent biker in'' [[The Brothers Solomon]]'' (which featured SNL castmate [[Will Forte]] in one of the film's co-leading roles) and, most famously, as Officer Slater in the [[Judd Apatow]] produced'' [[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yuan|first1=Jada|title=Bill Hader on His Sundance Hit Skeleton Twins, Lip-Synching With Kristen Wiig, and Breaking Into Drama|url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/01/bill-hader-sundance-skeleton-twins-interview.html|website=Vulture|accessdate=August 3, 2016|date=January 30, 2014}}</ref> His role in ''Superbad'' helped boost his public awareness and allowed him to appear on mainstream programs like ''Total Request Live'', ''The Tonight Show'', and MTV's ''Video Music Awards''.\n\nHader worked as a [[creative consultant]] and producer on ''[[South Park]]'', beginning in the series' [[South Park (season 12)|12th season]].<ref>Toal, Drew (March 26, 2009). [http://newyork.timeout.com/articles/hot-seat/72706/bill-hader \"The Hot Seat: Bill Hader\"]. ''[[Time Out New York]]''.</ref> His involvement in the series stems from his friendship with [[Matt Stone]]; the two held a similar sense of humor and Hader began going on writers' retreats with the staff.<ref name=\"i14\"/> He began working on the program hoping to learn story structure.<ref name=\"fcc14\"/> Hader is among the series producers to win the 2009 Emmy Award for Best Animated Series.<ref name=\"huffpost2010\"/> He also appeared on the commentary recorded for the 2009 Blu-ray edition of ''[[South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut]]'', and the [[Comedy Central]] special ''[[6 Days to Air]]'', a documentary filmed during production of the 2011 ''South Park'' episode \"[[HumancentiPad]].\" Hader rejoined the writing staff for ''South Park'' for its [[South Park (season 17)|17th season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://splitsider.com/2013/07/bill-hader-is-writing-for-south-park-full-time-this-season/|title=Bill Hader Is Writing for 'South Park' Full-Time This Season \u2013 Splitsider|work=Splitsider|access-date=July 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209032111/http://splitsider.com/2013/07/bill-hader-is-writing-for-south-park-full-time-this-season/|archive-date=February 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Hader won a 2008 Peabody Award in Political Satire for his participation in ''Saturday Night Live''.<ref name=\"huffpost2010\"/> He also appeared on the MTV prank series ''[[Punk'd]]'' and voiced an array of characters on the second season of the [[Adult Swim]] animated series ''[[Xavier: Renegade Angel]]''. He also made several short films, including ''Back in the Day'', ''Sounds Good to Me: Remastering the Sting'', and ''The Jeannie Tate Show'', with ''SNL'' writer Liz Cackowski and then-wife Maggie Carey.\n\nIn 2008, Hader starred in, and cowrote with [[Simon Rich]], the web series ''The Line'' on [[Crackle (company)|Crackle]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Bill Hader Video! \"The Line\" Episode 1 | publisher = The Deadbolt | url = http://billhaderonline.com/main/2008/07/22/bill-hader-video-the-line-episode-1/ | date = July 22, 2008 | accessdate = 2009-02-27 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090313122853/http://billhaderonline.com/main/2008/07/22/bill-hader-video-the-line-episode-1/ | archivedate = March 13, 2009 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Hader lent his voice to the [[audiobook]] of [[Sarah Vowell]]'s ''[[The Wordy Shipmates]]''. Also in 2008, Hader appeared on ''[[Tim and Eric Awesome Show]]'' impersonating the recurring character James Quall on the episode \"Jazz\". He appeared in two other Apatow projects: ''[[Forgetting Sarah Marshall]] '' and ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]''. He also starred alongside [[Ben Stiller]], [[Robert Downey, Jr.]] and [[Tom Cruise]] in the action comedy ''[[Tropic Thunder]]''. Hader re-teamed with ''Superbad'' director [[Greg Mottola]] in the comedy films ''[[Adventureland (film)|Adventureland]]'' (2009) and ''[[Paul (film)|Paul]]'' (2011). He also lent his voice to his first video game role, the mega hit [[Grand Theft Auto IV]], which also featured his SNL castmates Jason Sudeikis and [[Fred Armisen]].\n\nHader and ''SNL'' castmate [[Seth Meyers]] penned a Spider-Man one-off entitled ''The Short Halloween''. It was illustrated by [[Kevin Maguire (artist)|Kevin Maguire]] and came out May 29, 2009. It was given three and a half out of five stars by Benjamin Birdie of [[Comic Book Resources]].<ref>Birdie, Benjamin (May 28, 2009). [http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=user_review&id=1058 \"Spider-Man: The Short Halloween #1\"]. [[Comic Book Resources]].</ref> He made a small appearance in the 2009 comedy film ''[[Year One (film)|Year One]]'', with [[Jack Black]] and [[Michael Cera]]. Hader lent his voice to the critically acclaimed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1196077-cloudy_with_a_chance_of_meatballs/|title=Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs|date=September 18, 2009|work=rottentomatoes.com}}</ref> [[Sony Pictures Animation]] film ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (film)|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs]]'', as well as its [[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs 2|2013 sequel]], playing the lead role of Flint Lockwood as well as his invention in the films, the FLDSMDFR. He voiced a gazelle in ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]'' and appeared in the fantasy film ''[[Night at the Museum: Battle of the Smithsonian]]'' as [[Major General]] [[George Armstrong Custer]]. In April 2009, Hader was a part of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'''s list of \"Comedy's New Legends\".<ref>[http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/features/2009/04/comedians-portfolio200904?slide=4#globalNav \"Laughing Matter: Comedy's New Legends\"] ''Vanity Fair'', April 2009.</ref>\n\nHader took on the voice role of Professor Impossible on the fourth season of ''[[The Venture Brothers]]'' (2010\u20132013), a part originated by [[Stephen Colbert]]. In the game ''[[Grand Theft Auto IV]]'', he played Wilson Taylor, Sr., (on in-game radio show: ''Pacemaker''). He voiced the Pod in the ''[[Aqua Teen Hunger Force]]'' episode \"IAMAPOD\", as well as Hitler in the episode \"Der Inflatable Fuhrer\". Hader played Kevin, [[Matt Damon]]'s copilot, in the live episode of ''[[30 Rock]],'' recorded October 14, 2010. He portrayed \"The Voice\" in the action comedy film ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'' (2010), the disembodied voice that pops up during certain moments of the film's video game-inspired fight scenes. He also had a small cameo as the voice of the USS ''Vengeance'' computer in the science fiction film ''[[Star Trek Into Darkness]]'' (2013). Hader hosted the 2011 and 2012 seasons of ''Essentials, Jr.'' on [[Turner Classic Movies]]. In the series premiere of the comedy series ''[[The Mindy Project]]'', he guest-starred as Mindy's ex-boyfriend Tom McDougall. His character returned later in the first season. Hader voiced Dr. Malocchio in the [[Hulu]] animated comedy series ''[[The Awesomes]]''. In 2013, Hader replaced [[Robert Downey, Jr.]], as the voice of [[Mr. Peanut]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/popcandy/2013/07/02/bill-hader-mr-peanut-planters/2483269/|title=Bill Hader's new role: Mr. Peanut|publisher=}}</ref> He has a severe peanut allergy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peanutallergy.com/videos/peanut-allergy/comedian-bill-hader-talks-peanut-allergy-scare-video|title=Comedian Bill Hader Talks Peanut Allergy Scare (Video)|date=January 30, 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHader decided to leave ''SNL'' after eight seasons, informing cast and crew of his decision in February 2013. He came to the conclusion that he needed to leave when his then-wife and he were constantly having to travel to Los Angeles for work, which made it difficult for their children.<ref name=\"pb13\"/><ref name=\"i14\" /> His final episode was on May 18, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Hader to Leave ''Saturday Night Live''|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/15/arts/television/bill-hader-to-leave-saturday-night-live.html?partner=rss&emc=rss&smid=tw-nytimes&_r=0|newspaper=NY Times|accessdate=May 14, 2013|first=Dave|last=Itzkoff|date=May 14, 2013}}</ref> \"It was a hard decision, but it has to happen at some point,\" he told reporters. \"It got to a point where I said, 'Maybe it's just time to go.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdjournal.com/2013/05/15/bill-hader-leaves-saturday-night-live/|title=Bill Hader Leaves Saturday Night Live \u2013 JD Journal|author=Daniel June|date=May 15, 2013|work=jdjournal.com}}</ref> On October 11, 2014, Hader returned as host with musical guest [[Hozier (musician)|Hozier]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perkins|first1=Dennis|title=''Saturday Night Live'': \"Bill Hader/Hozier\"|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/saturday-night-live-bill-haderhozier-210385|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=August 2, 2016|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> and on March 17, 2018 with musical guest [[Arcade Fire]].\n\n===2014\u2013present: Film roles and ''Barry''===\n\n[[File:Bill Hader, 2013 San Diego Comic Con-cropped-2.jpg|thumb|upright|Hader at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]\n\nHader starred in a dramatic role in the 2014 film ''[[The Skeleton Twins]]'', opposite [[Kristen Wiig]], with whom he worked on ''Saturday Night Live''. The film won for 'Best Screenplay' at the [[Sundance Film Festival]]. In 2015, Hader voiced the character of Fear in the critically acclaimed Disney-Pixar film, ''[[Inside Out (2015 film)|Inside Out]]'', and was attached to voice a dinosaur in the Pixar film ''[[The Good Dinosaur]]''. However, Hader, alongside [[John Lithgow]], [[Lucas Neff]], [[Neil Patrick Harris]] and [[Judy Greer]], left the project after their characters were redesigned.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thill |first=Scott |url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/pixar/good-dinosaur-cast-114419.html |title=Pixar Suddenly Reshuffles 'The Good Dinosaur' Cast |publisher=Cartoonbrew.com |date=2015-06-15 |accessdate=2016-12-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Hader appeared in ''[[Brooklyn Nine-Nine]]'' as the captain of the 99th Precinct.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hDX5gINaZws|title=Brooklyn Nine-Nine Season 3 Promo \"New Captain\" (HD)|first=|last=tvpromosdb|date=September 6, 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> Also in 2015, Hader reunited with fellow ''SNL'' alumnus Fred Armisen for the [[IFC (U.S. TV network)|IFC]] mockumentary series ''[[Documentary Now!]]'', wherein he was an actor and a writer.\n\nIn December 2015, Drew McWeeny of [[HitFix]] reported that the voice of [[BB-8]] was supplied by Hader and [[Ben Schwartz]], both credited as \"BB-8 vocal consultants\" in the film. The voice was created by Abrams manipulating their voices through a [[talkbox]], attached to an [[iPad]] running a sound-effects app.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hitfix.com/motion-captured/wait-a-minute-who-played-the-voice-of-bb-8-in-star-wars-the-force-awakens |title=Wait a minute... who played the voice of BB-8 in ''Star Wars: The Force Awakens''? |work=[[HitFix]] |first=Drew |last=McWeeny |authorlink=Drew McWeeny |date=December 15, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref> Hader also voiced multiple characters in [[YouTube]] channel [[Bad Lip Reading]]'s parodies of the [[Original trilogy|''Star Wars'' original trilogy]].\n\nHader had his first leading man role in the romantic-comedy opposite [[Amy Schumer]] in ''[[Trainwreck (film)|Trainwreck]]'' (2015) and continued  in these romantic roles as a former college boyfriend to best friend of [[Greta Gerwig]]'s title character in ''[[Maggie's Plan]]'' (2015). Hader voiced Alpha 5 in the 2017 film version of ''[[Power Rangers (film)|Power Rangers]]''.<ref>[http://www.ew.com/article/2016/09/22/bill-hader-power-rangers-alpha-5 \"Bill Hader to play robot sidekick Alpha 5 in Power Rangers\"] ''Entertainment Weekly'', September 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Hader co-created (with [[Alec Berg]]) and began starring in the [[HBO]] dark comedy series ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]'', for which he received eight [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations as producer, writer, director, and actor. He won Emmys for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]] in both 2018 and 2019 and received consecutive nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]] for its first two seasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0352778/awards|title=Bill Hader|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Hader starred in the supernatural horror film ''[[It \u2013 Chapter Two|It: Chapter Two]]'' as [[Richie Tozier]] (sharing the role with [[Finn Wolfhard]]), alongside [[Jessica Chastain]], [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]], [[Isaiah Mustafa]], [[Jay Ryan (actor)|Jay Ryan]], [[James Ransone]], and [[James McAvoy]]. Hader received acclaim for his performance, with many believing the role showed Hader's capability of performing film roles outside of comedy.<ref name=\"facebook.com/gamesradarplus\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/it-2-cast/|title=It 2 has revealed its grown up stars, and you're gonna like this roll call|work=facebook.com/gamesradarplus/|access-date=2018-05-22|language=en}}</ref> In 2019, he voiced Leonard in ''[[The Angry Birds Movie 2]]'', Axel the Carnie in ''[[Toy Story 4]]'', The Wanderer in 4 episodes of ''[[The Dark Crystal: Age of Resistance]]'', and played Nick Kringle in [[Noelle (2019 film)|''Noelle'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0352778/|title=Bill Hader|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nHader has stated that his comedy influences are [[Monty Python]], [[Alan Alda]], [[Woody Allen]], [[Mel Brooks]] and [[Eddie Murphy]].<ref name=\"huffpost07-14\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2006, Hader married writer-director [[Maggie Carey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://people.com/parents/saturday-night-lives-bill-hader-welcomes-a-daughter/| title=Saturday Night Live's Bill Hader Welcomes a Daughter |first=Sarah|last=Michaud |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=October 12, 2009|accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> They have three daughters together, Hannah, born October 6, 2009,<ref name=us2012>{{cite news | url = http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-moms/news/bill-hader-welcomes-a-daughter-2012307| title=Bill Hader, Wife Maggie Carey Welcome Daughter Harper!|date=July 30, 2012 |work=[[Us Weekly]] | first=Zach| last=Johnson| accessdate =November 18, 2014}}</ref> Harper, born July 28, 2012,<ref name=us2012 /> and Hayley, born November 15, 2014.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-moms/news/bill-hader-wife-maggie-carey-welcome-baby-girl-hayley-hader-20141811| title=Bill Hader, Wife Maggie Carey Welcome Third Child, Baby Girl Hayley clementine Hader!| date=November 18, 2014 |first= Sierra|last= Marquina |first2= Brody |last2=Brown|work=Us Weekly|accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> Hader and Carey announced their separation in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/tv/bill-hader-maggie-carey-divorcing/|title=Saturday Night Live's Bill Hader and Wife Maggie Carey Are Divorcing -|work=People|first1=Michele| last1=Corrison|first2=Julie|last2=Jordan|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=April 1, 2018}}</ref> Hader filed for divorce in December 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-snl-alum-bill-hader-divorcing-after-11-1513958226-htmlstory.html|title=SNL alum Bill Hader Divorcing after 11 years|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 22, 2017|accessdate=April 1, 2018|first= Nardine|last=Saad}}</ref> The uncontested divorce reached a settlement on March 1, 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/bill-hader-reaches-divorce-settlement-with-ex-wife-maggie-carey-97737|title=Bill Hader Reaches Divorce Settlement With Ex-Wife Maggie Carey|publisher=|accessdate=October 6, 2018}}</ref> and they were restored to single persons on June 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/tv/bill-hader-settles-divorce-maggie-carey/|title=Bill Hader Reaches Divorce Settlement with Ex-Wife Maggie Carey|publisher=|accessdate=October 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHader is an avid reader who has said, \"I didn't really go to college, which is probably why I enjoy reading the classics.\" Works by [[Fyodor Dostoevsky|Dostoevsky]] and [[William Faulkner|Faulkner]], as well as [[Richard Ford]], [[Jun'ichir\u014d Tanizaki|Junichiro Tanizaki]], and [[George Saunders]] are among the books on his shelves.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/20/books/review/bill-hader-by-the-book.html|title=Bill Hader: By the Book|date=2014-07-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Bill Hader filmography}}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n===Primetime Emmy Award===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| 2009\n| rowspan=2| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program]]\n| rowspan=2| ''[[South Park]]''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n|2011\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2012\n| rowspan=2| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n| rowspan=2| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2013\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2014\n| rowspan=2|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program]] \n| rowspan=2| ''South Park''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2015\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n|''Saturday Night Live''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2016\n| rowspan=2| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Variety Sketch Series|Outstanding Variety Sketch Series]]\n| rowspan=2|''[[Documentary Now!]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2017\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program]]\n|''South Park''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=5| 2018 \n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n| ''Saturday Night Live''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n| rowspan=8| ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=5| 2019\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Variety Sketch Series|Outstanding Variety Sketch Series]]\n| ''Documentary Now!''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n===Golden Globe Award===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n|2019\n|rowspan=2|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]]\n|rowspan=2|''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2020\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Screen Actors Guild Award===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2019\n|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Comedy Series|Male Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n|rowspan=4|''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Ensemble in a Comedy Series]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2020\n|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Comedy Series|Male Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Ensemble in a Comedy Series]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Writers Guild of America Award===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n|2017\n|Comedy/Variety - Sketch Series\n|''[[Documentary Now!]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" |2019\n|[[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Comedy Series|Television: Comedy Series]]\n|rowspan=\"4\" | ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Episodic Comedy|Television: Episodic Comedy]]\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|[[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: New Series|Television: New Series]]\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|2020\n|[[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Comedy Series|Television: Comedy Series]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Directors Guild of America Award===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n|2019\n| rowspan=2|[[Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding Directing \u2013 Comedy Series|Directing \u2013 Comedy Series]]\n| rowspan=2|''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]''\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|2020\n|{{won}}\n|}\n\n===Producers Guild of America Award===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n|2019 \n| rowspan=2|[[Producers Guild of America Award for Best Episodic Comedy|Best Episodic Comedy]]\n| rowspan=2|''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2020\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n===Critics Awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Awards\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n|2009\n|[[Gotham Awards]]\n|[[Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Ensemble Cast|Best Ensemble Cast]]\n|''[[Adventureland (film)|Adventureland]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2014\n|[[Gotham Awards]]\n|[[Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[The Skeleton Twins]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Women Film Critics Circle Awards|Women's Film Critics Circle Award]]\n|Best On-Screen Couple\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Critics' Choice Television Award]]\n|Best Actor in a Comedy Series\n|''[[Documentary Now!]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2018\n|[[IndieWire|IndieWire Honors]]\n|Performance Award\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2019\n|[[Critics Choice Television Awards]]\n|[[Best Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n|rowspan=\"3\" | ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]''\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|[[American Film Institute#AFI Awards|AFI Awards]]\n|AFI Television Programs of the Year\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|2020\n|[[Critics Choice Television Awards]]\n|[[Best Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bill Hader}}\n*{{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Bill Hader\n|list =\n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Actor in a Comedy Series}}\n{{DirectorsGuildofAmericaOutstandingDirectingComedySeries}}\n{{EmmyAward ComedyLeadActor}}\n{{Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy}}\n{{WritersGuildofAmericaEpisodicComedyScreenplay 2010s}}\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hader, Bill}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American impressionists (entertainers)]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Danish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American sketch comedians]]\n[[Category:American stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award winners]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Scottsdale Community College alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Lead Actor in a Comedy Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor, comedian, writer, and producer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Bill Hader\n| image        = File:Bill Hader (29419489470) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size   = 200px\n| caption      = Hader in September 2016\n| birth_name   = William Thomas Hader Jr.\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1978|6|7}}\n| birth_place  = [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| occupation   = {{flatlist|\n*Actor\n*comedian\n*writer\n*producer\n*director\n}}\n| years_active = 1999\u2013present\n| alma_mater   = [[Scottsdale Community College]]\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Maggie Carey]]|2006|2018|reason=div}}\n| children      = Hannah Hader<br>Harper Hader<br>Hayley Hader}}\n'''William Thomas Hader Jr.''' (born June 7, 1978)<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/bill-hader-57635941/| work= [[Hollywood.com]] | title=Bill Hader {{!}} Biography and Filmography {{!}} 1978| accessdate= May 5, 2017}}</ref> is an American actor, comedian, writer, producer, and director. He rose to fame as a cast member on the [[NBC]] variety series ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (2005\u20132013) for which he received four [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations and a  [[Peabody Award]].\n\nHader has had supporting roles in the films ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' (2007), ''[[Tropic Thunder]]'' (2008), ''[[Forgetting Sarah Marshall]]'' (2008), ''[[Night at the Museum: Battle of the Smithsonian]]'' (2009), ''[[Paul (film)|Paul]]'' (2011), ''[[Men in Black 3]]'' (2012) and leading roles in ''[[The Skeleton Twins]]'' (2014), ''[[Trainwreck (film)|Trainwreck]]'' (2015) and ''[[It Chapter Two]]'' (2019) as an adult [[Richie Tozier]]. He has voiced lead characters in the  ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (franchise)|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs]]'' franchise (2009\u20132014), ''[[Inside Out (2015 film)|Inside Out]]'' (2015), the ''[[The Angry Birds Movie|Angry Birds]]'' films (2016, 2019), ''[[Sausage Party]]'' (2016), ''[[Ralph Breaks the Internet]]'' (2018) and supporting roles in ''[[Turbo (2013 film)|Turbo]]'' (2013), ''[[Monsters University]]'' (2013) and ''[[Finding Dory]]'' (2016).\n\nDuring his time on ''Saturday Night Live'', Hader became known for his impressions and his character [[Stefon]] in the ''[[Weekend Update]]'' segments. He is the co-creator, writer, and producer of the [[IFC (U.S. TV channel)|IFC]] mockumentary comedy series ''[[Documentary Now!]]'' (2015\u2013present), in which he stars alongside [[Fred Armisen]]. In 2018, Hader created and began starring as the titular assassin in the [[HBO]] dark comedy series ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]'', which earned him two Emmy Awards for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]] and consecutive nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]] for its first two seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/2018-emmy-nominations-list-all-nominees-1202425072/|title=Emmy Nominations: 'Game Of Thrones' Tops Noms, With Netflix & HBO Leading Way \u2013 Full List|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=July 12, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=October 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHader was born and raised in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], the son of Sherri Renee (n\u00e9e Patton) and William Thomas Hader.<ref name=fdnr1>''[[Finding Your Roots]]'', January 26, 2016, PBS</ref><ref name=dla>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Michael |title=Hader about to be a proud papa|newspaper=Tulsa World|date=September 18, 2009|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/site/printerfriendlystory.aspx?articleid=20090918_283_D1_BillHa114485|accessdate=November 15, 2010}}</ref> His father owned an air-freight company and worked as a restaurant manager, truck driver and occasional [[stand-up comedian]];<ref name=\"nyt2007\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/23/movies/23itzk.html?_r=0 |title=A 'Superbad' Geek's Progress |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 23, 2007 |first=Dave |last=Itzkoff |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref> his mother was a dance teacher.<ref name=\"rollingstone2014\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/features/bill-hader-trades-stefon-for-serious-drama-in-the-skeleton-twins-20140911 |title=Bill Hader Trades Stefon for Serious Drama in 'The Skeleton Twins' |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=September 11, 2014 |first=Jonah |last=Weiner |accessdate=October 13, 2014 }}</ref> He has two younger sisters, Katie and Kara.<ref name=dla/> His surname originates in Germany; his ancestry includes German, Danish, Irish, and English.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/weta/finding-your-roots/blog/bill-haders-interactive-family-tree/ |title=Bill Hader's Interactive Family Tree &#124; Finding Your Roots |publisher=PBS |date=2016-01-28 |accessdate=2016-12-21}}</ref><ref>https://www.businessinsider.com/pbs-finding-your-roots-bill-hader-2016-1?IR=T</ref>\n\nHader attended Patrick Henry Elementary School, [[Edison Preparatory School|Edison Junior High]], and [[Cascia Hall Preparatory School]].<ref>Michael Smith, [http://www.tulsaworld.com/entertainment/spot/article.aspx?articleID=070817_8_ES14_Itwas70410 \"Super Glad: Native Tulsan Bill Hader moves from 'SNL' success to big-budget film roles,\"] ''[[Tulsa World]]'', August 17, 2007.</ref><ref>Michael Smith, [http://www.tulsaworld.com/spot/article.aspx?subjectid=243&articleid=20090403_282_D1_JasonP931046 \"Talking about Tulsa days: Bill Hader finally found a vocation in comedy\"], ''[[Tulsa World]]'', April 3, 2009.</ref> He had \"a hard time focusing on class\" and was always \"joking around\". Though he was not hated by classmates, he felt he never truly fit in and filled his time watching movies and reading.<ref name=\"pb13\"/> He appreciated [[Monty Python]], [[British comedy]], and the films of [[Mel Brooks]] and [[Woody Allen]],<ref name=\"i14\">{{cite news|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/bill-hader#_|title=Interview: Bill Hader|author=[[Danny McBride]]|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|accessdate=November 26, 2015}}</ref> many of which he was introduced to through his father.<ref name=\"pb13\"/> He made short films with friends and starred in a school production of ''[[The Glass Menagerie]]''.<ref name=\"i14\"/>\n\nHe was unable to gain admission to top [[film school]]s because of his \"abysmal\" grades, so he instead enrolled at [[The Art Institute of Phoenix]],<ref name=\"07ok\">Gene Triplett, [http://newsok.com/article/3105814 \"Funny things about Bill Hader: Growing up in Tulsa as 'movie nerd' gave comic actor material,\"] ''[[The Oklahoman]]'', August 17, 2007.</ref> and later [[Scottsdale Community College]].<ref name=\"pb13\"/> Hader has mentioned that his very first job was selling Christmas trees. He also worked as an usher at a movie theater in nearby [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]], which allowed him to see films for free. He was fired for [[Spoiler (media)|spoiling]] the ending of the 1997 film ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' to noisy patrons.<ref name=\"huffpost07-14\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/07/13/bill-hader-mike-sacks-interview-poking-a-dead-frog-_n_5582142.html |title=Bill Hader Got Fired For Spoiling The End Of 'Titanic' & 10 More Facts You Didn't Know |work=The Huffington Post |date=July 14, 2014 |first=Katla |last=McGlynn |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"ifc14\"/> At Scottsdale, he met Nicholas Jasenovec, the director of ''[[Paper Heart (film)|Paper Heart]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/watch-extensive-2-1-2-hour-talk-with-bill-hader-about-his-career-films-and-more-20140813 |title=Watch: Extensive 2 1/2 Hour Talk With Bill Hader About His Career, Films And More |work=Indie Wire |date=August 13, 2014 |first=Tess |last=Hoffman |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1999\u20132004: Early career===\nHader's aspirations of becoming a filmmaker<ref name=\"huffpost07-14\"/> eventually led him to drop out of college and move to Los Angeles in 1999.<ref name=\"nyt2007\"/><ref name=\"pb13\">{{cite news|title=20Q: Bill Hader|work=[[Playboy]]|author=Rob Tannenbaum|date=September 2013|url=http://playboy.co.za/20q-bill-hader|accessdate=November 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126175804/http://playboy.co.za/20q-bill-hader|archive-date=November 26, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> His parents were supportive of his decision to move, and Hader used the money they had originally saved for his college education to cover his living expenses when he arrived in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"i14\"/> He found work as a [[production assistant]] (PA) while scouring the back pages of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'',<ref name=\"g14\"/> and he hoped to advance far enough to become an assistant director.<ref name=\"g14\"/> He spent much of his young adulthood \"lonely and underemployed,\" filling large amounts of spare time with movie marathons.<ref name=\"g14\">{{cite news|title=Bill Hader's Day Off|author=Amos Barhsad|publisher=[[Grantland.com]]|date=August 25, 2014|url=http://grantland.com/features/bill-hader-saturday-night-live-snl-week/|accessdate=November 26, 2015}}</ref> He regularly worked 18-hour days as a PA, having little time to pursue his creative ambitions.<ref name=\"i14\"/> He worked as a PA on the DVD ''[[Empire of Dreams: The Story of the Star Wars Trilogy]]''; the feature films ''[[James Dean (film)|James Dean]]'',<ref name=\"jamesfrancoesquire\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.esquire.com/features/james-franco/james-franco-bill-hader-0910 |title=Four Introductions to James Franco |magazine=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |first=Bill |last=Hader |date=August 11, 2010 |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref> ''[[Spider-Man (2002 film)|Spider-Man]]'',<ref name=\"jamesfrancoesquire\"/> and ''[[Collateral Damage (film)|Collateral Damage]]'';<ref name=\"nyt2007\"/> as well as a post-production assistant on [[VH1]] television's ''[[The Surreal Life]]''.<ref name=\"huffpost2010\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aoltv.com/2010/09/24/snl-star-bill-hader-talks-the-new-season-jon-hamms-return-an/ |title='SNL' Star Bill Hader Talks the New Season, Jon Hamm's Return and His 'Surreal Life' Experience with Corey Feldman |work=The Huffington Post |date=September 24, 2010 |first=Kim |last=Potts |accessdate=October 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921063946/http://www.aoltv.com/2010/09/24/snl-star-bill-hader-talks-the-new-season-jon-hamms-return-an/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Hader briefly worked as a PA and stage manager on [[Playboy TV]]'s ''[[Night Calls]]'';<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifc.com/fix/2014/09/bill-hader-playboy-tv-kimmel |title=BILL HADER TALKS ABOUT HIS PLAYBOY TV PAST ON KIMMEL |publisher=IFC |date=September 10, 2014 |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/tv/2014/09/bill-hader-jimmy-kimmel-playboy-call-in-show/ |title=Here's Bill Hader Describing What It Was Like To Work The Phones for a Playboy Call-In Sex Show |publisher=Uproxx |date=September 10, 2014 |first=Kris |last=Maske |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"nyobserver2014\">{{cite news|url=http://observer.com/2014/09/funnyman-bill-hader-on-going-serious-you-have-to-empty-yourself-a-little-bit/ |title=Funnyman Bill Hader on Going Serious: 'You Have to Empty Yourself a Little Bit' |newspaper=New York Observer |date=September 11, 2014 |first=Vinnie |last=Mancuso |accessdate=October 22, 2014 }}</ref> but quit, as he feared it would disappoint his parents.<ref name=\"ifc14\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ifc.com/shows/documentary-now/blog/2015/08/the-many-weird-jobs-of-bill-hader|title=5 Jobs You Probably Didn't Know Bill Hader Once Had|author=Steele|first=Brian|date=August 24, 2015|website=|publisher=[[IFC (TV channel)|IFC.com]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref> He eventually quit being a PA altogether after a bad experience shooting ''[[The Scorpion King]]''.<ref name=\"g14\"/>\n\nHader subsequently secured a job working as a nighttime assistant editor at post-production facility [[Triage Entertainment]].<ref name=\"i14\"/><ref name=\"g14\"/> He invested money into his own short film, but was too embarrassed to release it. Shortly thereafter, Hader and his then-longtime girlfriend broke up.<ref name=\"fcc14\">{{cite news|title=How Bill Hader Went from Production Assistant to ''SNL'' Hero to Leading Man|author=Joe Berkowitz|date=September 24, 2014|work=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]|url=http://www.fastcocreate.com/3036180/then-and-now/how-bill-hader-went-from-production-assistant-to-snl-hero-to-leading-man|accessdate=November 26, 2015}}</ref> Desperate for a change, he began attending comedy classes with friends at [[improvisational comedy]] enterprise [[the Second City]] in March 2003.<ref name=\"07ok\"/> He quickly realized that comedy was the creative outlet that he had needed since he made the decision to leave higher education behind,<ref name=\"i14\"/> and soon Hader, his new compatriot in comedy Matt Offerman, and their two friends and fellow humor enthusiasts Eric Filipkowski and Mel Cowan, elected to form their own sketch comedy group.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hollywoodphony.wordpress.com/2008/05/11/my-father-jocko-filipkowski/|title=My father, Jocko Filipkowski|date=2008-05-11|work=hollywoodphony|access-date=2018-04-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Christening their group ''Animals from the Future'', the four frequently appeared to small audiences at backyard shows in Van Nuys.<ref name=\"g14\"/> Matt's brother, actor [[Nick Offerman]], told his wife, [[Megan Mullally]], about the group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/08/22/159766489/bill-hader-on-sketch-comedy-his-love-of-old-films |title=Bill Hader on Sketch Comedy, His Love of Old Films |publisher=NPR |date=August 22, 2012 |accessdate=October 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theringer.com/tv/2018/3/19/17131052/bill-hader-barry-show-hbo|title=The Name's Hader \u2026 Bill Hader|work=The Ringer|access-date=2018-04-20}}</ref> After attending one of the group's backyard appearances, Mullally told Hader of her intention to discuss him with [[Lorne Michaels]] of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (''SNL''). As a result of Mullally's recommendation, Hader was asked to audition for the show and he soon flew to New York to audition for a group of ''SNL'' producers. Hader had no impressions prepared when he was invited to audition. He was nervous and struggled to display his strengths during the audition. This resulted in his spontaneous imitation of an elderly Italian man he had once overheard. The impression would later become the first of Hader's many recurring characters on the show: Vinny Vedecci.<ref name=\"g14\" /> As a result of the audition, Hader got an agent and manager.<ref name=\"pb13\"/> Just before he was officially invited to begin work on ''SNL'', Hader was working as an assistant editor on ''[[Iron Chef America]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gawker.com/5784918/bill-hader-shares-his-road-to-saturday-night-live |title=Bill Hader Shares His Road to Saturday Night Live |author=Whitney Jefferson |publisher=Gawker Media |work=Gawker |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115013528/http://gawker.com/5784918/bill-hader-shares-his-road-to-saturday-night-live |archivedate=January 15, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n===2005\u20132013: Breakthrough and ''Saturday Night Live''===\nHader was hired as a featured player and made his debut on the show on October 1, 2005. His first role was as a [[psychologist]] giving his views about life and death during the emergency landing of [[JetBlue Airways Flight 292]]. He felt he had gone from \"preschool to [[Harvard]].\"<ref name=\"fcc14\"/> He became the \"impressions guy,\" hoping to fill a utility-player role \"like his hero [[Phil Hartman]]\".<ref name=\"g14\"/> Hader has said that he performed impersonations of teachers and friends when he was growing up but did not do impersonations of famous people until his ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' audition.<ref>[http://billhaderonline.com/main/2007/10/08/bill-hader-does-interview-with-bill-hader-online \"Bill Hader does interview with BHO!\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009113151/http://billhaderonline.com/main/2007/10/08/bill-hader-does-interview-with-bill-hader-online/ |date=October 9, 2011 }}. Retrieved October 14, 2007.</ref> His list of impressions includes [[Vincent Price]] in the Variety Vault sketches, [[Keith Morrison]], [[Harvey Fierstein]], [[Al Pacino]], [[Rick Perry]], [[John Malkovich]], [[James Carville]], [[Julian Assange]], [[Eliot Spitzer]], [[Alan Alda]], [[Clint Eastwood]], and [[Charlie Sheen]]. On July 19, 2012, Hader received his first nomination for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series]] for his work on ''SNL''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/emmys-2012-saturday-night-live-bill-hader-351992|title=Emmys 2012: 'SNL's' Bill Hader Shocked By Nomination, Says It Wasn't on His Radar|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=July 19, 2012|first=Philiana|last=Ng|date=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/19/emmy-nominees-bill-hader-of-saturday-night-live/ | work=The New York Times | first=Dave | last=Itzkoff | title=Emmy Nominees: Bill Hader of 'Saturday Night Live' | date=July 19, 2012}}</ref> He is the first male ''SNL'' cast member to receive this nomination since Eddie Murphy in 1984.\n\nDespite this, Hader suffered from anxiety and sleep problems during his tenure at the program.<ref name=\"pb13\"/> He never felt \"truly comfortable\" throughout his first four seasons.<ref name=\"g14\"/> He was insecure that he had less comedy experience than his peers. He would often not sleep on Fridays before the show, and would feel light-headed prior to broadcasts.<ref name=\"pb13\"/> He was neurotic regarding his performances; Hader called his early performances \"rigid\".<ref name=\"g14\"/> On one occasion, he began having a [[panic attack]], live on air, while impersonating Julian Assange. It was the final episode of 2010 (hosted by [[Jeff Bridges]]), and Hader remembered; \"It felt like someone was sitting on my chest. I couldn't breathe, I started sweating. I thought, ''This is not good \u2014 abort! abort!''\"<ref name=\"pb13\"/> Hader is also prone to [[Migraine|migraines,]] and also suffered one live on air; [[Jason Sudeikis]] had to guide him on and offstage as he couldn't see anything.<ref>{{Citation|last=Paul Ofcharsky|title=Bill Hader's Migraines|date=2018-03-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gPzcmsBMDL0&t=1m39s|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref> Lorne Michaels tried to put him at ease by remarking to him, \"You can work here as long as you want,\" after the incident.<ref name=\"g14\"/>\n\nAmong the characters Hader played was [[Stefon]], ''[[Weekend Update]]''{{'}}s flamboyant New York City correspondent, whose recommendations consist solely of bizarre nightclubs involving nightmarish characters. Stefon is in love with and married to [[Seth Meyers]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jue|first1=Teresa|title=Bill Hader discusses the origins of Stefon on 'Seth Meyers'|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/09/16/bill-hader-discusses-the-origins-of-stefon-on-late-night-with-seth-meyers|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=August 2, 2016|date=September 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Busis|first1=Hillary|title='Saturday Night Live': A full directory of Stefon's favorite clubs. (This post has EVERYTHING.)|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2013/05/17/saturday-night-live-stefon-clubs-everything|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=August 2, 2016|date=May 17, 2013}}</ref> He was originally a one-shot character on a season-34 sketch where a screenwriter named David Zolesky (played by [[Ben Affleck]]) invites his estranged brother Stefon over to pitch a family-friendly sports drama about a college student who bonds with his grandfather so he can try out for the college football team.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Franks|first1=Jonathan|title=Stefon Flashback: In His SNL Debut with Ben Affleck, He Was Just Plain Scary!|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/1536610/stefon-flashback-snl-debut/|website=[[Inquisitr]]|accessdate=August 2, 2016|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> He is based on two people ''SNL'' writer [[John Mulaney]] and Hader met: a wannabe club owner who always invited Mulaney to weird underground clubs and a barista Hader met who looks, speaks, and dresses like Stefon.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dalton|first1=Christine|title=John Mulaney Reveals The Story Behind Stefon On 'Late Night'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/04/john-mulaney-stefon-late-night_n_5092351.html|website=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=August 2, 2016|date=April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter his film debut ''[[You, Me and Dupree]]'' (2006), Hader had a wide range of roles in 2007, such as [[Katherine Heigl]]'s character's editor at [[E!]] in ''[[Knocked Up]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kirk|first1=Jeremy|title=35 Things We Learned From the 'Knocked Up' Commentary|url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/35-things-we-learned-from-the-knocked-up-commentary-f2a65c8e511c|website=Film School Rejects|accessdate=August 3, 2016|date=October 6, 2011}}</ref> the acid-taking mechanic Dave in ''[[Hot Rod (2007 film)|Hot Rod]]'' alongside'' SNL'' castmate [[Andy Samberg]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Edwin|title=A Definitive Ranking of the 11 Funniest Hot Rod Scenes|url=https://www.beamly.com/tv-film/definitive-ranking-11-funniest-hot-rod-scenes|publisher=[[Beamly]]|accessdate=August 3, 2016|date=September 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612015717/https://www.beamly.com/tv-film/definitive-ranking-11-funniest-hot-rod-scenes|archive-date=June 12, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> a recumbent biker in'' [[The Brothers Solomon]]'' (which featured SNL castmate [[Will Forte]] in one of the film's co-leading roles) and, most famously, as Officer Slater in the [[Judd Apatow]] produced'' [[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yuan|first1=Jada|title=Bill Hader on His Sundance Hit Skeleton Twins, Lip-Synching With Kristen Wiig, and Breaking Into Drama|url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/01/bill-hader-sundance-skeleton-twins-interview.html|website=Vulture|accessdate=August 3, 2016|date=January 30, 2014}}</ref> His role in ''Superbad'' helped boost his public awareness and allowed him to appear on mainstream programs like ''Total Request Live'', ''The Tonight Show'', and MTV's ''Video Music Awards''.\n\nHader worked as a [[creative consultant]] and producer on ''[[South Park]]'', beginning in the series' [[South Park (season 12)|12th season]].<ref>Toal, Drew (March 26, 2009). [http://newyork.timeout.com/articles/hot-seat/72706/bill-hader \"The Hot Seat: Bill Hader\"]. ''[[Time Out New York]]''.</ref> His involvement in the series stems from his friendship with [[Matt Stone]]; the two held a similar sense of humor and Hader began going on writers' retreats with the staff.<ref name=\"i14\"/> He began working on the program hoping to learn story structure.<ref name=\"fcc14\"/> Hader is among the series producers to win the 2009 Emmy Award for Best Animated Series.<ref name=\"huffpost2010\"/> He also appeared on the commentary recorded for the 2009 Blu-ray edition of ''[[South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut]]'', and the [[Comedy Central]] special ''[[6 Days to Air]]'', a documentary filmed during production of the 2011 ''South Park'' episode \"[[HumancentiPad]].\" Hader rejoined the writing staff for ''South Park'' for its [[South Park (season 17)|17th season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://splitsider.com/2013/07/bill-hader-is-writing-for-south-park-full-time-this-season/|title=Bill Hader Is Writing for 'South Park' Full-Time This Season \u2013 Splitsider|work=Splitsider|access-date=July 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209032111/http://splitsider.com/2013/07/bill-hader-is-writing-for-south-park-full-time-this-season/|archive-date=February 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Hader won a 2008 Peabody Award in Political Satire for his participation in ''Saturday Night Live''.<ref name=\"huffpost2010\"/> He also appeared on the MTV prank series ''[[Punk'd]]'' and voiced an array of characters on the second season of the [[Adult Swim]] animated series ''[[Xavier: Renegade Angel]]''. He also made several short films, including ''Back in the Day'', ''Sounds Good to Me: Remastering the Sting'', and ''The Jeannie Tate Show'', with ''SNL'' writer Liz Cackowski and then-wife Maggie Carey.\n\nIn 2008, Hader starred in, and cowrote with [[Simon Rich]], the web series ''The Line'' on [[Crackle (company)|Crackle]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Bill Hader Video! \"The Line\" Episode 1 | publisher = The Deadbolt | url = http://billhaderonline.com/main/2008/07/22/bill-hader-video-the-line-episode-1/ | date = July 22, 2008 | accessdate = 2009-02-27 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090313122853/http://billhaderonline.com/main/2008/07/22/bill-hader-video-the-line-episode-1/ | archivedate = March 13, 2009 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Hader lent his voice to the [[audiobook]] of [[Sarah Vowell]]'s ''[[The Wordy Shipmates]]''. Also in 2008, Hader appeared on ''[[Tim and Eric Awesome Show]]'' impersonating the recurring character James Quall on the episode \"Jazz\". He appeared in two other Apatow projects: ''[[Forgetting Sarah Marshall]] '' and ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]''. He also starred alongside [[Ben Stiller]], [[Robert Downey, Jr.]] and [[Tom Cruise]] in the action comedy ''[[Tropic Thunder]]''. Hader re-teamed with ''Superbad'' director [[Greg Mottola]] in the comedy films ''[[Adventureland (film)|Adventureland]]'' (2009) and ''[[Paul (film)|Paul]]'' (2011). He also lent his voice to his first video game role, the mega hit [[Grand Theft Auto IV]], which also featured his SNL castmates Jason Sudeikis and [[Fred Armisen]].\n\nHader and ''SNL'' castmate [[Seth Meyers]] penned a Spider-Man one-off entitled ''The Short Halloween''. It was illustrated by [[Kevin Maguire (artist)|Kevin Maguire]] and came out May 29, 2009. It was given three and a half out of five stars by Benjamin Birdie of [[Comic Book Resources]].<ref>Birdie, Benjamin (May 28, 2009). [http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=user_review&id=1058 \"Spider-Man: The Short Halloween #1\"]. [[Comic Book Resources]].</ref> He made a small appearance in the 2009 comedy film ''[[Year One (film)|Year One]]'', with [[Jack Black]] and [[Michael Cera]]. Hader lent his voice to the critically acclaimed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1196077-cloudy_with_a_chance_of_meatballs/|title=Cloudy With a Chance of Meatballs|date=September 18, 2009|work=rottentomatoes.com}}</ref> [[Sony Pictures Animation]] film ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (film)|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs]]'', as well as its [[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs 2|2013 sequel]], playing the lead role of Flint Lockwood as well as his invention in the films, the FLDSMDFR. He voiced a gazelle in ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]'' and appeared in the fantasy film ''[[Night at the Museum: Battle of the Smithsonian]]'' as [[Major General]] [[George Armstrong Custer]]. In April 2009, Hader was a part of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'''s list of \"Comedy's New Legends\".<ref>[http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/features/2009/04/comedians-portfolio200904?slide=4#globalNav \"Laughing Matter: Comedy's New Legends\"] ''Vanity Fair'', April 2009.</ref>\n\nHader took on the voice role of Professor Impossible on the fourth season of ''[[The Venture Brothers]]'' (2010\u20132013), a part originated by [[Stephen Colbert]]. In the game ''[[Grand Theft Auto IV]]'', he played Wilson Taylor, Sr., (on in-game radio show: ''Pacemaker''). He voiced the Pod in the ''[[Aqua Teen Hunger Force]]'' episode \"IAMAPOD\", as well as Hitler in the episode \"Der Inflatable Fuhrer\". Hader played Kevin, [[Matt Damon]]'s copilot, in the live episode of ''[[30 Rock]],'' recorded October 14, 2010. He portrayed \"The Voice\" in the action comedy film ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'' (2010), the disembodied voice that pops up during certain moments of the film's video game-inspired fight scenes. He also had a small cameo as the voice of the USS ''Vengeance'' computer in the science fiction film ''[[Star Trek Into Darkness]]'' (2013). Hader hosted the 2011 and 2012 seasons of ''Essentials, Jr.'' on [[Turner Classic Movies]]. In the series premiere of the comedy series ''[[The Mindy Project]]'', he guest-starred as Mindy's ex-boyfriend Tom McDougall. His character returned later in the first season. Hader voiced Dr. Malocchio in the [[Hulu]] animated comedy series ''[[The Awesomes]]''. In 2013, Hader replaced [[Robert Downey, Jr.]], as the voice of [[Mr. Peanut]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/popcandy/2013/07/02/bill-hader-mr-peanut-planters/2483269/|title=Bill Hader's new role: Mr. Peanut|publisher=}}</ref> He has a severe peanut allergy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peanutallergy.com/videos/peanut-allergy/comedian-bill-hader-talks-peanut-allergy-scare-video|title=Comedian Bill Hader Talks Peanut Allergy Scare (Video)|date=January 30, 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHader decided to leave ''SNL'' after eight seasons, informing cast and crew of his decision in February 2013. He came to the conclusion that he needed to leave when his then-wife and he were constantly having to travel to Los Angeles for work, which made it difficult for their children.<ref name=\"pb13\"/><ref name=\"i14\" /> His final episode was on May 18, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Hader to Leave ''Saturday Night Live''|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/15/arts/television/bill-hader-to-leave-saturday-night-live.html?partner=rss&emc=rss&smid=tw-nytimes&_r=0|newspaper=NY Times|accessdate=May 14, 2013|first=Dave|last=Itzkoff|date=May 14, 2013}}</ref> \"It was a hard decision, but it has to happen at some point,\" he told reporters. \"It got to a point where I said, 'Maybe it's just time to go.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdjournal.com/2013/05/15/bill-hader-leaves-saturday-night-live/|title=Bill Hader Leaves Saturday Night Live \u2013 JD Journal|author=Daniel June|date=May 15, 2013|work=jdjournal.com}}</ref> On October 11, 2014, Hader returned as host with musical guest [[Hozier (musician)|Hozier]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perkins|first1=Dennis|title=''Saturday Night Live'': \"Bill Hader/Hozier\"|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/saturday-night-live-bill-haderhozier-210385|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=August 2, 2016|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> and on March 17, 2018 with musical guest [[Arcade Fire]].\n\n===2014\u2013present: Film roles and ''Barry''===\n\n[[File:Bill Hader, 2013 San Diego Comic Con-cropped-2.jpg|thumb|upright|Hader at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]\n\nHader starred in a dramatic role in the 2014 film ''[[The Skeleton Twins]]'', opposite [[Kristen Wiig]], with whom he worked on ''Saturday Night Live''. The film won for 'Best Screenplay' at the [[Sundance Film Festival]]. In 2015, Hader voiced the character of Fear in the critically acclaimed Disney-Pixar film, ''[[Inside Out (2015 film)|Inside Out]]'', and was attached to voice a dinosaur in the Pixar film ''[[The Good Dinosaur]]''. However, Hader, alongside [[John Lithgow]], [[Lucas Neff]], [[Neil Patrick Harris]] and [[Judy Greer]], left the project after their characters were redesigned.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thill |first=Scott |url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/pixar/good-dinosaur-cast-114419.html |title=Pixar Suddenly Reshuffles 'The Good Dinosaur' Cast |publisher=Cartoonbrew.com |date=2015-06-15 |accessdate=2016-12-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Hader appeared in ''[[Brooklyn Nine-Nine]]'' as the captain of the 99th Precinct.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hDX5gINaZws|title=Brooklyn Nine-Nine Season 3 Promo \"New Captain\" (HD)|first=|last=tvpromosdb|date=September 6, 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> Also in 2015, Hader reunited with fellow ''SNL'' alumnus Fred Armisen for the [[IFC (U.S. TV network)|IFC]] mockumentary series ''[[Documentary Now!]]'', wherein he was an actor and a writer.\n\nIn December 2015, Drew McWeeny of [[HitFix]] reported that the voice of [[BB-8]] was supplied by Hader and [[Ben Schwartz]], both credited as \"BB-8 vocal consultants\" in the film. The voice was created by Abrams manipulating their voices through a [[talkbox]], attached to an [[iPad]] running a sound-effects app.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hitfix.com/motion-captured/wait-a-minute-who-played-the-voice-of-bb-8-in-star-wars-the-force-awakens |title=Wait a minute... who played the voice of BB-8 in ''Star Wars: The Force Awakens''? |work=[[HitFix]] |first=Drew |last=McWeeny |authorlink=Drew McWeeny |date=December 15, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref> Hader also voiced multiple characters in [[YouTube]] channel [[Bad Lip Reading]]'s parodies of the [[Original trilogy|''Star Wars'' original trilogy]].\n\nHader had his first leading man role in the romantic-comedy opposite [[Amy Schumer]] in ''[[Trainwreck (film)|Trainwreck]]'' (2015) and continued  in these romantic roles as a former college boyfriend to best friend of [[Greta Gerwig]]'s title character in ''[[Maggie's Plan]]'' (2015). Hader voiced Alpha 5 in the 2017 film version of ''[[Power Rangers (film)|Power Rangers]]''.<ref>[http://www.ew.com/article/2016/09/22/bill-hader-power-rangers-alpha-5 \"Bill Hader to play robot sidekick Alpha 5 in Power Rangers\"] ''Entertainment Weekly'', September 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Hader co-created (with [[Alec Berg]]) and began starring in the [[HBO]] dark comedy series ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]'', for which he received eight [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations as producer, writer, director, and actor. He won Emmys for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]] in both 2018 and 2019 and received consecutive nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]] for its first two seasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0352778/awards|title=Bill Hader|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Hader starred in the supernatural horror film ''[[It \u2013 Chapter Two|It: Chapter Two]]'' as [[Richie Tozier]] (sharing the role with [[Finn Wolfhard]]), alongside [[Jessica Chastain]], [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]], [[Isaiah Mustafa]], [[Jay Ryan (actor)|Jay Ryan]], [[James Ransone]], and [[James McAvoy]]. Hader received acclaim for his performance, with many believing the role showed Hader's capability of performing film roles outside of comedy.<ref name=\"facebook.com/gamesradarplus\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/it-2-cast/|title=It 2 has revealed its grown up stars, and you're gonna like this roll call|work=facebook.com/gamesradarplus/|access-date=2018-05-22|language=en}}</ref> In 2019, he voiced Leonard in ''[[The Angry Birds Movie 2]]'', Axel the Carnie in ''[[Toy Story 4]]'', The Wanderer in 4 episodes of ''[[The Dark Crystal: Age of Resistance]]'', and played Nick Kringle in [[Noelle (2019 film)|''Noelle'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0352778/|title=Bill Hader|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nHader has stated that his comedy influences are [[Monty Python]], [[Alan Alda]], [[Woody Allen]], [[Mel Brooks]] and [[Eddie Murphy]].<ref name=\"huffpost07-14\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2006, Hader married writer-director [[Maggie Carey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://people.com/parents/saturday-night-lives-bill-hader-welcomes-a-daughter/| title=Saturday Night Live's Bill Hader Welcomes a Daughter |first=Sarah|last=Michaud |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=October 12, 2009|accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> They have three daughters together, Hannah, born October 6, 2009,<ref name=us2012>{{cite news | url = http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-moms/news/bill-hader-welcomes-a-daughter-2012307| title=Bill Hader, Wife Maggie Carey Welcome Daughter Harper!|date=July 30, 2012 |work=[[Us Weekly]] | first=Zach| last=Johnson| accessdate =November 18, 2014}}</ref> Harper, born July 28, 2012,<ref name=us2012 /> and Hayley, born November 15, 2014.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-moms/news/bill-hader-wife-maggie-carey-welcome-baby-girl-hayley-hader-20141811| title=Bill Hader, Wife Maggie Carey Welcome Third Child, Baby Girl Hayley clementine Hader!| date=November 18, 2014 |first= Sierra|last= Marquina |first2= Brody |last2=Brown|work=Us Weekly|accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> Hader and Carey announced their separation in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/tv/bill-hader-maggie-carey-divorcing/|title=Saturday Night Live's Bill Hader and Wife Maggie Carey Are Divorcing -|work=People|first1=Michele| last1=Corrison|first2=Julie|last2=Jordan|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=April 1, 2018}}</ref> Hader filed for divorce in December 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-snl-alum-bill-hader-divorcing-after-11-1513958226-htmlstory.html|title=SNL alum Bill Hader Divorcing after 11 years|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 22, 2017|accessdate=April 1, 2018|first= Nardine|last=Saad}}</ref> The uncontested divorce reached a settlement on March 1, 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/bill-hader-reaches-divorce-settlement-with-ex-wife-maggie-carey-97737|title=Bill Hader Reaches Divorce Settlement With Ex-Wife Maggie Carey|publisher=|accessdate=October 6, 2018}}</ref> and they were restored to single persons on June 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/tv/bill-hader-settles-divorce-maggie-carey/|title=Bill Hader Reaches Divorce Settlement with Ex-Wife Maggie Carey|publisher=|accessdate=October 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHader is an avid reader who has said, \"I didn't really go to college, which is probably why I enjoy reading the classics.\" Works by [[Fyodor Dostoevsky|Dostoevsky]] and [[William Faulkner|Faulkner]], as well as [[Richard Ford]], [[Jun'ichir\u014d Tanizaki|Junichiro Tanizaki]], and [[George Saunders]] are among the books on his shelves.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/20/books/review/bill-hader-by-the-book.html|title=Bill Hader: By the Book|date=2014-07-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Bill Hader filmography}}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n===Primetime Emmy Award===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| 2009\n| rowspan=2| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program]]\n| rowspan=2| ''[[South Park]]''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n|2011\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2012\n| rowspan=2| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n| rowspan=2| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2013\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2014\n| rowspan=2|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program]] \n| rowspan=2| ''South Park''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2015\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n|''Saturday Night Live''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2016\n| rowspan=2| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Variety Sketch Series|Outstanding Variety Sketch Series]]\n| rowspan=2|''[[Documentary Now!]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2017\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program]]\n|''South Park''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=5| 2018 \n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n| ''Saturday Night Live''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]]\n| rowspan=8| ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Out